# ============================================================
# SECTION 1: MODULES, HOMOMORPHISMS AND EXACT SEQUENCES
# ============================================================

# Def 1.1: Left R-Module
write_yaml "left-r-module" "left-r-module" "Left R-Module" "左R-模" "definition" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Definition 1.1"
write_tex "left-r-module" 'Let $R$ be a ring. A (left) $R$-module is an additive abelian group $A$ together with a function $R \times A \to A$ (the image of $(r,a)$ being denoted by $ra$) such that for all $r,s \in R$ and $a,b \in A$:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $r(a + b) = ra + rb$.
\item[(ii)] $(r + s)a = ra + sa$.
\item[(iii)] $r(sa) = (rs)a$.
\end{enumerate}
If $R$ has an identity element $1_R$ and
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(iv)] $1_R a = a$ for all $a \in A$,
\end{enumerate}
then $A$ is said to be a \emph{unitary} $R$-module. If $R$ is a division ring, then a unitary $R$-module is called a (left) \emph{vector space}.'
write_intro "left-r-module" "An $R$-module generalizes the notion of an abelian group (which is a $\mathbb{Z}$-module) by allowing the scalars to come from an arbitrary ring $R$. The definition requires the additive abelian group structure plus a scalar multiplication satisfying distributivity and associativity axioms. When $R$ has identity and the module is unitary, the identity acts as expected; when $R$ is a division ring, we recover the definition of a vector space."

# Def 1.2: R-Module Homomorphism
write_yaml "r-module-homomorphism" "r-module-homomorphism" "R-Module Homomorphism" "R-模同态" "definition" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Definition 1.2"
write_tex "r-module-homomorphism" 'Let $A$ and $B$ be modules over a ring $R$. A function $f : A \to B$ is an \emph{$R$-module homomorphism} provided that for all $a, c \in A$ and $r \in R$:
\[
f(a + c) = f(a) + f(c) \quad \text{and} \quad f(ra) = rf(a).
\]
If $R$ is a division ring, then an $R$-module homomorphism is called a \emph{linear transformation}.'
write_intro "r-module-homomorphism" "An $R$-module homomorphism is a structure-preserving map between $R$-modules: it respects both the additive group structure (as a group homomorphism) and the scalar multiplication. The kernel and image of a module homomorphism are submodules. When $R$ is a division ring, module homomorphisms coincide with linear transformations of vector spaces."

# Def 1.3: Submodule
write_yaml "submodule" "submodule" "Submodule" "子模" "definition" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Definition 1.3"
write_tex "submodule" 'Let $R$ be a ring, $A$ an $R$-module and $B$ a nonempty subset of $A$. $B$ is a \emph{submodule} of $A$ provided that $B$ is an additive subgroup of $A$ and $rb \in B$ for all $r \in R$, $b \in B$. A submodule of a vector space over a division ring is called a \emph{subspace}.'
write_intro "submodule" "A submodule is a subset of a module that is itself a module under the same operations. The condition requires closure under addition and under scalar multiplication by elements of the ring. The kernel and image of any module homomorphism are submodules, and intersections of submodules are again submodules."

# Def 1.4: Submodule Generated by Subset
write_yaml "submodule-generated-by-subset" "submodule-generated-by-subset" "Submodule Generated by a Subset" "子集生成的子模" "definition" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Definition 1.4"
write_tex "submodule-generated-by-subset" 'If $X$ is a subset of a module $A$ over a ring $R$, then the intersection of all submodules of $A$ containing $X$ is called the \emph{submodule generated by $X$} (or \emph{spanned by $X$}). If $X$ is finite and generates the module $B$, $B$ is said to be \emph{finitely generated}. If $X = \emptyset$, then the submodule generated by $X$ is the zero submodule.'
write_intro "submodule-generated-by-subset" "The submodule generated by a subset $X$ is the smallest submodule containing $X$, obtained as the intersection of all submodules containing $X$. When $X$ is finite, the resulting module is called finitely generated. If the ring has identity and the module is unitary, the generated submodule consists of all finite linear combinations of elements of $X$ with coefficients in $R$."

# Thm 1.6: Quotient Module
write_yaml "quotient-module" "quotient-module" "Quotient Module" "商模" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Theorem 1.6"
write_tex "quotient-module" 'Let $B$ be a submodule of a module $A$ over a ring $R$. Then the quotient group $A/B$ is an $R$-module with the action of $R$ on $A/B$ given by:
\[
r(a + B) = ra + B \quad \text{for all } r \in R, a \in A.
\]
The map $\pi : A \to A/B$ given by $a \mapsto a + B$ is an $R$-module epimorphism with kernel $B$.'
write_intro "quotient-module" "The quotient module $A/B$ generalizes quotient groups to the module setting. The scalar multiplication is well-defined because $B$ is a submodule, guaranteeing that the coset $ra + B$ depends only on the coset $a + B$. The canonical projection $\pi$ is a surjective module homomorphism with kernel exactly $B$."
write_proof "quotient-module" "IV.1" "direct-verification" 'Since $A$ is an additive abelian group, $B$ is a normal subgroup, and $A/B$ is a well-defined abelian group. If $a + B = a'\' + B$, then $a - a'\' \in B$. Since $B$ is a submodule, $ra - ra'\' = r(a - a'\') \in B$ for all $r \in R$. Thus $ra + B = ra'\' + B$ by Corollary I.4.3 and the action of $R$ on $A/B$ is well defined. The remainder of the proof verifies the module axioms and that $\pi$ is an epimorphism with kernel $B$.'

# Thm 1.7: Isomorphism Theorems for Modules
write_yaml "isomorphism-theorems-for-modules" "isomorphism-theorems-for-modules" "Isomorphism Theorems for Modules" "模的同构定理" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Theorem 1.7"
write_tex "isomorphism-theorems-for-modules" 'If $R$ is a ring and $f: A \to B$ is an $R$-module homomorphism, then there is an $R$-module isomorphism $A/\operatorname{Ker} f \cong \operatorname{Im} f$.'
write_intro "isomorphism-theorems-for-modules" "The First Isomorphism Theorem for modules states that any module homomorphism induces an isomorphism between the quotient of the domain by the kernel and the image. More generally, all isomorphism theorems for groups (Theorems I.5.6 through I.5.12) carry over to modules, mutatis mutandis, by verifying at each stage that subgroups and homomorphisms are in fact submodules and module homomorphisms."

# Thm 1.9: Second and Third Isomorphism Theorems
write_yaml "second-third-isomorphism-theorems-modules" "second-third-isomorphism-theorems-modules" "Second and Third Isomorphism Theorems for Modules" "模的第二和第三同构定理" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Theorem 1.9"
write_tex "second-third-isomorphism-theorems-modules" 'Let $B$ and $C$ be submodules of a module $A$ over a ring $R$.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] There is an $R$-module isomorphism $B/(B \cap C) \cong (B + C)/C$;
\item[(ii)] if $C \subset B$, then $B/C$ is a submodule of $A/C$, and there is an $R$-module isomorphism $(A/C)/(B/C) \cong A/B$.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "second-third-isomorphism-theorems-modules" "The Second Isomorphism Theorem (i) relates the intersection and sum of submodules: the quotient of a submodule by its intersection with another is isomorphic to their sum modulo the second. The Third Isomorphism Theorem (ii) states that quotients of quotients simplify: $(A/C)/(B/C) \cong A/B$ when $C \subset B \subset A$."
write_proof "second-third-isomorphism-theorems-modules" "IV.1" "group-theoretic-transfer" 'The proof follows from the corresponding group-theoretic isomorphism theorems (Corollaries I.5.9 and I.5.10), with the additional verification that all subgroup structures involved are actually submodules and that the isomorphisms respect the $R$-module structure.'

# Thm 1.10: Correspondence Theorem for Modules
write_yaml "correspondence-theorem-for-modules" "correspondence-theorem-for-modules" "Correspondence Theorem for Modules" "模的对应定理" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Theorem 1.10"
write_tex "correspondence-theorem-for-modules" 'If $R$ is a ring and $B$ is a submodule of an $R$-module $A$, then there is a one-to-one correspondence between the set of all submodules of $A$ containing $B$ and the set of all submodules of $A/B$, given by $C \mapsto C/B$. Hence every submodule of $A/B$ is of the form $C/B$, where $C$ is a submodule of $A$ which contains $B$.'
write_intro "correspondence-theorem-for-modules" "The Correspondence Theorem establishes a bijection between submodules of $A$ containing $B$ and submodules of the quotient $A/B$. This is the module-theoretic analogue of Theorem I.5.11 and is fundamental for understanding the submodule structure of quotient modules."
write_proof "correspondence-theorem-for-modules" "IV.1" "group-theoretic-transfer" 'The proof follows from Theorem I.5.11 and Corollary I.5.12, with the verification that the correspondence preserves the $R$-module structure.'

# Thm 1.11: Direct Product and Sum of Modules
write_yaml "direct-product-and-sum-of-modules" "direct-product-and-sum-of-modules" "Direct Product and Direct Sum of Modules" "模的直积与直和" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Theorem 1.11"
write_tex "direct-product-and-sum-of-modules" 'Let $R$ be a ring and $\{A_i \mid i \in I\}$ a nonempty family of $R$-modules, $\prod_{i \in I} A_i$ the direct product of the abelian groups $A_i$, and $\sum_{i \in I} A_i$ the direct sum of the abelian groups $A_i$.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $\prod_{i \in I} A_i$ is an $R$-module with the action of $R$ given by $r\{a_i\} = \{ra_i\}$.
\item[(ii)] $\sum_{i \in I} A_i$ is a submodule of $\prod_{i \in I} A_i$.
\item[(iii)] For each $k \in I$, the canonical projection $\pi_k: \prod A_i \to A_k$ is an $R$-module epimorphism.
\item[(iv)] For each $k \in I$, the canonical injection $\iota_k: A_k \to \sum A_i$ is an $R$-module monomorphism.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "direct-product-and-sum-of-modules" "Direct products and direct sums of modules are defined componentwise, extending the abelian group constructions. The direct product $\prod A_i$ is the Cartesian product with componentwise operations, while the direct sum $\sum A_i$ is the submodule of elements with only finitely many nonzero components. The canonical projections and injections are module homomorphisms."

# Thm 1.12: Product Universal Property
write_yaml "product-universal-property-modules" "product-universal-property-modules" "Universal Property of the Direct Product of Modules" "模的直积的万有性质" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Theorem 1.12"
write_tex "product-universal-property-modules" 'If $R$ is a ring, $\{A_i \mid i \in I\}$ a family of $R$-modules, $C$ an $R$-module, and $\{\varphi_i : C \to A_i \mid i \in I\}$ a family of $R$-module homomorphisms, then there is a unique $R$-module homomorphism $\varphi : C \to \prod_{i \in I} A_i$ such that $\pi_i \varphi = \varphi_i$ for all $i \in I$. The direct product is uniquely determined up to isomorphism by this property.'
write_intro "product-universal-property-modules" "The direct product $\prod A_i$ satisfies the universal property of a categorical product in the category of $R$-modules: given a family of homomorphisms from a module $C$ to each $A_i$, there is a unique homomorphism from $C$ to the product making all diagrams commute. This universal property determines the product up to isomorphism."

# Thm 1.13: Coproduct Universal Property
write_yaml "coproduct-universal-property-modules" "coproduct-universal-property-modules" "Universal Property of the Direct Sum of Modules" "模的直和的万有性质" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Theorem 1.13"
write_tex "coproduct-universal-property-modules" 'If $R$ is a ring, $\{A_i \mid i \in I\}$ a family of $R$-modules, $D$ an $R$-module, and $\{\psi_i : A_i \to D \mid i \in I\}$ a family of $R$-module homomorphisms, then there is a unique $R$-module homomorphism $\psi : \sum A_i \to D$ such that $\psi \iota_i = \psi_i$ for all $i \in I$. The direct sum is uniquely determined up to isomorphism by this property.'
write_intro "coproduct-universal-property-modules" "The direct sum $\sum A_i$ satisfies the universal property of a categorical coproduct in the category of $R$-modules. Given a family of homomorphisms from each $A_i$ to a module $D$, there is a unique homomorphism from the direct sum to $D$ extending all of them. The map is given by $\psi(\{a_i\}) = \sum_i \psi_i(a_i)$, where the sum is over the finite set of indices with $a_i \neq 0$."
write_proof "coproduct-universal-property-modules" "IV.1" "universal-property" 'By Theorem I.8.5 there is a unique abelian group homomorphism $\psi : \sum A_i \to D$ with the desired property, given by $\psi(\{a_i\}) = \sum_i \psi_i(a_i)$, where the sum is taken over the finite set of indices $i$ such that $a_i \neq 0$. It is easy to see that $\psi$ is an $R$-module map. Hence $\sum A_i$ is a coproduct in the category of $R$-modules (Definition I.7.4), and therefore, determined up to isomorphism by Theorem I.7.5.'

# Thm 1.15: Internal Direct Sum
write_yaml "internal-direct-sum-characterization" "internal-direct-sum-characterization" "Internal Direct Sum Characterization" "内直和的特征" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.1" "Theorem 1.15"
write_tex "internal-direct-sum-characterization" 'Let $R$ be a ring and $\{A_i \mid i \in I\}$ a family of submodules of an $R$-module $A$ such that
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $A$ is the sum of the family $\{A_i \mid i \in I\}$;
\item[(ii)] for each $k \in I$, $A_k \cap A_k^* = 0$, where $A_k^*$ is the sum of the family $\{A_i \mid i \neq k\}$.
\end{enumerate}
Then there is an isomorphism $A \cong \sum_{i \in I} A_i$.'
write_intro "internal-direct-sum-characterization" "A module $A$ is the internal direct sum of a family of submodules $\{A_i\}$ if it is generated by them and each submodule intersects the sum of the others trivially. Under these conditions, $A$ is isomorphic to the external direct sum of the $A_i$, and we say $A$ is the (internal) direct sum of the $A_i$. This generalizes the corresponding group-theoretic notion from Theorem I.8.6."

# Thm 1.17: Short Five Lemma
write_yaml "short-five-lemma" "short-five-lemma" "Short Five Lemma" "短五引理" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.1" "Theorem 1.17"
write_tex "short-five-lemma" 'Let $R$ be a ring and
\[
\begin{array}{ccccccccc}
0 & \to & A & \xrightarrow{f} & B & \xrightarrow{g} & C & \to & 0 \\
& & \alpha \downarrow & & \beta \downarrow & & \gamma \downarrow & & \\
0 & \to & A'\' & \xrightarrow{f\'\'} & B\'\' & \xrightarrow{g\'\'} & C\'\' & \to & 0
\end{array}
\]
a commutative diagram of $R$-modules and $R$-module homomorphisms with exact rows. Then:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] If $\alpha$ and $\gamma$ are monomorphisms, then $\beta$ is a monomorphism.
\item[(ii)] If $\alpha$ and $\gamma$ are epimorphisms, then $\beta$ is an epimorphism.
\item[(iii)] If $\alpha$ and $\gamma$ are isomorphisms, then $\beta$ is an isomorphism.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "short-five-lemma" "The Short Five Lemma is a fundamental diagram-chasing result for short exact sequences. It states that if two rows of a commutative diagram are short exact sequences and the outer vertical maps have a certain property (mono, epi, or iso), then the middle vertical map shares that property. It is a powerful tool for proving that maps are isomorphisms in homological algebra."
write_proof "short-five-lemma" "IV.1" "diagram-chase" '(i) Suppose $\alpha$ and $\gamma$ are monomorphisms. To show $\beta$ is a monomorphism, assume $\beta(b) = 0$ for $b \in B$. Then $\gamma g(b) = g\'\' \beta(b) = 0$. Since $\gamma$ is mono, $g(b) = 0$, so $b \in \operatorname{Ker} g = \operatorname{Im} f$. Write $b = f(a)$ for $a \in A$. Then $f\'\' \alpha(a) = \beta f(a) = \beta(b) = 0$. Since $f\'\'$ is mono and $\alpha$ is mono, $a = 0$, so $b = f(0) = 0$. Hence $\beta$ is mono.

(ii) Suppose $\alpha$ and $\gamma$ are epimorphisms. Let $b\'\' \in B\'\'$. Then $g\'\'(b\'\') \in C\'\'$. Since $\gamma$ is epi, $g\'\'(b\'\') = \gamma(c)$ for some $c \in C$. Since $g$ is epi, $c = g(b)$ for some $b \in B$. Then $g\'\' \beta(b) = \gamma g(b) = \gamma(c) = g\'\'(b\'\')$, so $g\'\'(\beta(b) - b\'\') = 0$. Thus $\beta(b) - b\'\' \in \operatorname{Ker} g\'\' = \operatorname{Im} f\'\'$, say $\beta(b) - b\'\' = f\'\'(a\'\')$ for $a\'\' \in A\'\'$. Since $\alpha$ is epi, $a\'\' = \alpha(a)$ for some $a \in A$. Consider $b - f(a) \in B$: $\beta(b - f(a)) = \beta(b) - \beta f(a) = \beta(b) - f\'\' \alpha(a) = \beta(b) - f\'\'(a\'\') = b\'\'$. Hence $\beta$ is epi.

(iii) is an immediate consequence of (i) and (ii).'

# Thm 1.18: Split Exact Sequence Characterization
write_yaml "split-exact-sequence-characterization" "split-exact-sequence-characterization" "Split Exact Sequence Characterization" "分裂正合列的特征" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.1" "Theorem 1.18"
write_tex "split-exact-sequence-characterization" 'Let $R$ be a ring and $0 \to A \xrightarrow{f} B \xrightarrow{g} C \to 0$ a short exact sequence of $R$-modules. Then the following conditions are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] There is an $R$-module homomorphism $h : C \to B$ such that $gh = 1_C$;
\item[(ii)] There is an $R$-module homomorphism $k : B \to A$ such that $kf = 1_A$;
\item[(iii)] The given sequence is isomorphic to the direct sum short exact sequence $0 \to A \to A \oplus C \to C \to 0$, and in particular $B \cong A \oplus C$.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "split-exact-sequence-characterization" "A short exact sequence is said to be split exact if it satisfies any of the three equivalent conditions: existence of a right inverse for the epimorphism (a section), existence of a left inverse for the monomorphism (a retraction), or isomorphism to the trivial direct sum sequence. Theorem 1.18 establishes the equivalence of these conditions and shows that a split short exact sequence decomposes the middle term as a direct sum."
write_proof "split-exact-sequence-characterization" "IV.1" "diagram-chase" '(i) $\Rightarrow$ (ii) Given $h : C \to B$ with $gh = 1_C$, define $k : B \to A$ as follows. For $b \in B$, note that $b - hg(b) \in \operatorname{Ker} g = \operatorname{Im} f$ since $g(b - hg(b)) = g(b) - ghg(b) = g(b) - g(b) = 0$. Thus $b - hg(b) = f(a)$ for a unique $a \in A$ (since $f$ is mono). Define $k(b) = a$. Verify $k$ is an $R$-module homomorphism and $kf = 1_A$.

(ii) $\Rightarrow$ (iii) Define $\varphi : B \to A \oplus C$ by $\varphi(b) = (k(b), g(b))$ and $\psi : A \oplus C \to B$ by $\psi(a,c) = f(a) + h(c)$. By the Short Five Lemma, $\varphi$ and $\psi$ are isomorphisms.

(iii) $\Rightarrow$ (i), (ii) Given an isomorphism to the direct sum sequence, the canonical injection $C \to A \oplus C$ and projection $A \oplus C \to A$ pull back to give the required maps.'

echo "=== Section 1 Complete ==="

