# Def: Linear Independence and Basis (unnumbered, between 1.18 and 2.1)
write_yaml "linear-independence-and-basis" "linear-independence-and-basis" "Linear Independence and Basis of a Module" "模的线性无关与基" "definition" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.2" "Definition (unnumbered)"
write_tex "linear-independence-and-basis" 'A subset $X$ of an $R$-module $A$ is said to be \emph{linearly independent} provided that for distinct $x_1, \ldots, x_n \in X$ and $r_i \in R$,
\[
r_1x_1 + r_2x_2 + \cdots + r_nx_n = 0 \Rightarrow r_i = 0 \text{ for every } i.
\]
A set that is not linearly independent is said to be \emph{linearly dependent}. If $A$ is generated as an $R$-module by a set $Y$, then we say that $Y$ \emph{spans} $A$. A linearly independent subset of $A$ that spans $A$ is called a \emph{basis} of $A$. The empty set is (vacuously) linearly independent and is a basis of the zero module.'
write_intro "linear-independence-and-basis" "These definitions generalize the familiar vector space notions to modules over an arbitrary ring. A subset is linearly independent if the only linear combination yielding zero is the trivial one. A basis is a linearly independent spanning set. Unlike vector spaces, not every module over an arbitrary ring possesses a basis; modules that do are called free modules."

# Thm 2.1: Free Module Characterization
write_yaml "free-module-characterization" "free-module-characterization" "Characterization of Free Modules" "自由模的特征" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.2" "Theorem 2.1"
write_tex "free-module-characterization" 'Let $R$ be a ring with identity. The following conditions on a unitary $R$-module $F$ are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $F$ has a nonempty basis;
\item[(ii)] $F$ is the internal direct sum of a family of cyclic $R$-modules, each of which is isomorphic as a left $R$-module to $R$;
\item[(iii)] $F$ is $R$-module isomorphic to a direct sum of copies of the left $R$-module $R$;
\item[(iv)] there exists a nonempty set $X$ and a function $\iota: X \to F$ with the following property: given any unitary $R$-module $A$ and function $f: X \to A$, there exists a unique $R$-module homomorphism $\bar{f}: F \to A$ such that $\bar{f}\iota = f$.
\end{enumerate}
An $R$-module $F$ satisfying any of these conditions is called a \emph{free $R$-module} on the set $X$.'
write_intro "free-module-characterization" "Theorem 2.1 gives four equivalent characterizations of a free module over a ring with identity: having a basis, being an internal direct sum of copies of $R$, being isomorphic to an external direct sum of copies of $R$, and satisfying the universal property of a free object in the category of $R$-modules. Condition (iv) is the categorical definition: a free module is a free object on a set."
write_proof "free-module-characterization" "IV.2" "cyclical-equivalence" '(i) $\Rightarrow$ (ii) Let $X$ be a basis of $F$. For each $x \in X$, $Rx$ is a cyclic submodule isomorphic to $R$ (via $r \mapsto rx$). Since $X$ is linearly independent and spans $F$, $F = \sum_{x \in X} Rx$ is an internal direct sum.

(ii) $\Rightarrow$ (iii) $F \cong \sum Rx \cong \sum R$ by definition of internal direct sum.

(iii) $\Rightarrow$ (i) The elements $\theta_x$ with $1_R$ in the $x$-th coordinate and $0$ elsewhere form a basis of $\sum R$.

(i) $\Rightarrow$ (iv) Given $X$ a basis and $f: X \to A$, define $\bar{f}(\sum r_i x_i) = \sum r_i f(x_i)$. Linear independence ensures well-definedness. Since $X$ generates $F$, any homomorphism is determined by its action on $X$, giving uniqueness.

(iv) $\Rightarrow$ (iii) Construct $\sum_{x \in X} R$ and use the free object property of both modules to establish isomorphism.'

# Cor 2.2: Homomorphic Image of Free Module
write_yaml "homomorphic-image-of-free-module" "homomorphic-image-of-free-module" "Every Module is a Homomorphic Image of a Free Module" "每个模都是自由模的同态像" "corollary" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.2" "Corollary 2.2"
write_tex "homomorphic-image-of-free-module" 'Every unitary module $A$ over a ring $R$ with identity is the homomorphic image of a free $R$-module. In fact, if $X$ is a set of generators of $A$ and $F$ is the free $R$-module on $X$, then the inclusion map $X \to A$ extends to an $R$-module epimorphism $F \to A$.'
write_intro "homomorphic-image-of-free-module" "Corollary 2.2 (also referenced as Theorem 2.2) states that every module can be expressed as a quotient of a free module. This is a fundamental structural result: pick a generating set, form the free module on that set, and extend the inclusion to a surjective homomorphism. This shows that free modules play the role of 'universal preimages' in module theory."
write_proof "homomorphic-image-of-free-module" "IV.2" "universal-property" 'Let $X$ be a set of generators of $A$ and $F$ the free $R$-module on the set $X$. Then the inclusion map $X \to A$ induces an $R$-module homomorphism $\bar{f}: F \to A$ such that $X \subset \operatorname{Im} \bar{f}$ (Theorem 2.1(iv)). Since $X$ generates $A$, we must have $\operatorname{Im} \bar{f} = A$.'

# Lemma 2.3: Maximal Linearly Independent Subset is Basis
write_yaml "maximal-linearly-independent-subset-is-basis" "maximal-linearly-independent-subset-is-basis" "Maximal Linearly Independent Subset is a Basis" "极大线性无关子集是基" "lemma" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.2" "Lemma 2.3"
write_tex "maximal-linearly-independent-subset-is-basis" 'A maximal linearly independent subset $X$ of a vector space $V$ over a division ring $D$ is a basis of $V$.'
write_intro "maximal-linearly-independent-subset-is-basis" "Lemma 2.3 states that in a vector space, any linearly independent subset that is maximal with respect to inclusion is necessarily a basis. The proof shows that if such a maximal set did not span, one could add a vector not in its span to get a larger linearly independent set, contradicting maximality."
write_proof "maximal-linearly-independent-subset-is-basis" "IV.2" "maximality-argument" 'Let $W$ be the subspace of $V$ spanned by $X$. Since $X$ is linearly independent and spans $W$, $X$ is a basis of $W$. If $W = V$, we are done. If not, then there exists a nonzero $a \in V$ with $a \notin W$. Consider $X \cup \{a\}$. If $ra + r_1x_1 + \cdots + r_nx_n = 0$ ($r, r_i \in D, x_i \in X$) and $r \neq 0$, then $a = r^{-1}(ra) = -r^{-1}r_1x_1 - \cdots - r^{-1}r_nx_n \in W$, which contradicts the choice of $a$. Hence $r = 0$, which implies $r_i = 0$ for all $i$ since $X$ is linearly independent. Thus $X \cup \{a\}$ is linearly independent, contradicting the maximality of $X$. Therefore $W = V$.'

# Thm 2.4: Every Vector Space Has a Basis
write_yaml "every-vector-space-has-basis" "every-vector-space-has-basis" "Every Vector Space Has a Basis" "每个向量空间都有基" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.2" "Theorem 2.4"
write_tex "every-vector-space-has-basis" 'Every vector space $V$ over a division ring $D$ has a basis. Consequently, every vector space is a free $D$-module.'
write_intro "every-vector-space-has-basis" "Theorem 2.4 is a fundamental result in linear algebra: every vector space, regardless of dimension, possesses a basis. The proof uses Zorn'\''s Lemma to find a maximal linearly independent subset of any spanning set, then invokes Lemma 2.3 to conclude it is a basis. This theorem implies that all vector spaces are free modules over their division ring of scalars."
write_proof "every-vector-space-has-basis" "IV.2" "zorns-lemma" 'Let $X$ be any subset that spans $V$ (e.g., $V$ itself). Partially order the set $S$ of all linearly independent subsets of $X$ by inclusion. Zorn'\''s Lemma implies the existence of a maximal linearly independent subset $Y$ of $X$. Every element of $X$ is a linear combination of elements of $Y$ (otherwise, as in Lemma 2.3, we could construct a linearly independent subset of $X$ that properly contains $Y$, contradicting maximality). Since $X$ spans $V$, so does $Y$. Hence $Y$ is a basis of $V$.'

# Thm 2.6: Infinite Basis Cardinality Invariance
write_yaml "infinite-basis-cardinality-invariance" "infinite-basis-cardinality-invariance" "Invariance of Cardinality for Infinite Bases" "无限基的基数不变性" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.2" "Theorem 2.6"
write_tex "infinite-basis-cardinality-invariance" 'Let $R$ be a ring with identity and $F$ a free $R$-module with an infinite basis $X$. Then every basis of $F$ has the same cardinality as $X$.'
write_intro "infinite-basis-cardinality-invariance" "For free modules over an arbitrary ring with identity, the cardinality of an infinite basis is invariant. The proof uses the fact that if $Y$ is another basis, each element of $Y$ is a finite linear combination of elements of $X$, which allows comparison of cardinalities via the Schroeder-Bernstein Theorem. Note that this is not true for finite bases over arbitrary rings (see Exercise 13)."
write_proof "infinite-basis-cardinality-invariance" "IV.2" "cardinality-comparison" "If $Y$ is another basis of $F$, we claim $Y$ is infinite. If $Y$ were finite, then since every element of $Y$ is a linear combination of finitely many elements of $X$, there would be a finite subset of $X$ generating $F$, contradicting the infinite linear independence of $X$. Let $K(Y)$ be the set of all finite subsets of $Y$. Define $f: X \to K(Y)$ by mapping each $x \in X$ to the finite set of basis elements from $Y$ appearing in its expression. Each finite subset of $Y$ has at most finitely many preimages (since $X$ is linearly independent), so $|X| \le |K(Y)| \cdot \aleph_0 = |Y|$ (since $Y$ is infinite). Interchanging $X$ and $Y$ gives $|Y| \le |X|$. By Schroeder-Bernstein, $|X| = |Y|$."

# Thm 2.7: Vector Space Basis Cardinality Invariance
write_yaml "vector-space-basis-cardinality-invariance" "vector-space-basis-cardinality-invariance" "Any Two Bases of a Vector Space Have the Same Cardinality" "向量空间任意两组基有相同的基数" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.2" "Theorem 2.7"
write_tex "vector-space-basis-cardinality-invariance" 'If $V$ is a vector space over a division ring $D$, then any two bases of $V$ have the same cardinality.'
write_intro "vector-space-basis-cardinality-invariance" "Theorem 2.7 establishes that the dimension of a vector space is well-defined. The proof handles the infinite case via Theorem 2.6, and the finite case via a replacement argument showing that if two finite bases have different sizes, one can substitute elements to derive a contradiction with linear independence."
write_proof "vector-space-basis-cardinality-invariance" "IV.2" "replacement-argument" 'If either basis is infinite, Theorem 2.6 applies. For finite bases $X = \{x_1,\ldots,x_n\}$ and $Y = \{y_1,\ldots,y_m\}$, suppose $m$ is minimal. Since $X$ spans, $y_m = \sum r_i x_i$. If $r_k$ is the first nonzero coefficient, then $x_k$ can be expressed in terms of $y_m$ and the other $x_i$, so $\{y_m, x_1,\ldots,x_{k-1},x_{k+1},\ldots,x_n\}$ spans $V$. Repeating this process replaces all $x_i$ with $y_j$ while preserving the spanning property and cardinality, showing $m = n$ by minimality.'

# Def 2.8: Rank and Invariant Dimension Property
write_yaml "rank-and-invariant-dimension-property" "rank-and-invariant-dimension-property" "Rank of a Free Module and the Invariant Dimension Property" "自由模的秩与不变维数性质" "definition" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.2" "Definition 2.8"
write_tex "rank-and-invariant-dimension-property" 'Let $R$ be a ring with identity. $R$ is said to have the \emph{invariant dimension property} (or \emph{IBN}, invariant basis number) if for every free $R$-module $F$, any two bases of $F$ have the same cardinality. In this case, the cardinal number $|X|$ of any basis $X$ of $F$ is called the \emph{rank} (or \emph{dimension}) of $F$, denoted $\operatorname{rank} F$.'
write_intro "rank-and-invariant-dimension-property" "A ring has the invariant dimension property (or invariant basis number) if the rank of every free module over it is well-defined. Not all rings have this property (Exercise 13 provides a counterexample). However, commutative rings with identity (Corollary 2.12) and division rings (Theorem 2.7) do have it. When well-defined, the rank generalizes the dimension of a vector space to free modules."

# Thm 2.10: Quotient of Free Module by Ideal
write_yaml "quotient-of-free-module-by-ideal" "quotient-of-free-module-by-ideal" "Quotient of a Free Module by an Ideal" "自由模关于理想的商" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.2" "Theorem 2.10"
write_tex "quotient-of-free-module-by-ideal" 'Let $R$ be a ring with identity, $I$ a proper ideal of $R$, and $F$ a free $R$-module with basis $X$. Then $F/IF$ is a free $R/I$-module with basis $\pi(X) = \{x + IF \mid x \in X\}$, where $\pi : F \to F/IF$ is the canonical epimorphism, and $|\pi(X)| = |X|$.'
write_intro "quotient-of-free-module-by-ideal" "Theorem 2.10 describes how a free module behaves under reduction modulo an ideal: $F/IF$ becomes a free module over the quotient ring $R/I$, and the image of a basis of $F$ under the canonical projection forms a basis of the quotient. This is fundamental for understanding extension and reduction of scalars."
write_proof "quotient-of-free-module-by-ideal" "IV.2" "basis-verification" 'If $u + IF \in F/IF$, write $u = \sum r_j x_j$ with $x_j \in X$. Then $u + IF = \sum (r_j + I)(x_j + IF) = \sum (r_j + I)\pi(x_j)$, so $\pi(X)$ generates $F/IF$. For linear independence: if $\sum (r_k + I)\pi(x_k) = 0$, then $\sum r_k x_k \in IF$, so $\sum r_k x_k = \sum s_j u_j$ with $s_j \in I$. Since each $u_j$ is a linear combination of elements of $X$, expanding gives an expression of $\sum r_k x_k$ as a linear combination with coefficients in $I$. By linear independence of $X$ over $R$, each $r_k \in I$, so $r_k + I = 0$ in $R/I$. Thus $\pi(X)$ is linearly independent over $R/I$.'

# Cor 2.12: Commutative Rings Have Invariant Dimension Property
write_yaml "commutative-rings-invariant-dimension" "commutative-rings-invariant-dimension" "Commutative Rings Have the Invariant Dimension Property" "交换环具有不变维数性质" "corollary" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.2" "Corollary 2.12"
write_tex "commutative-rings-invariant-dimension" 'Every commutative ring $R$ with identity has the invariant dimension property. In particular, if $F$ is a free $R$-module, any two bases of $F$ have the same cardinality.'
write_intro "commutative-rings-invariant-dimension" "Corollary 2.12 is a crucial result: over a commutative ring with identity, the rank of a free module is well-defined. The proof uses Theorem 2.10 and reduces to the vector space case by taking a maximal ideal $I$ of $R$ (which exists by Zorn'\''s Lemma), noting that $F/IF$ is a vector space over the field $R/I$ where dimension is well-defined by Theorem 2.7."
write_proof "commutative-rings-invariant-dimension" "IV.2" "reduction-to-field" 'Let $I$ be a maximal ideal of $R$ (exists by Zorn'\''s Lemma since $R$ has identity). Then $R/I$ is a field. If $X$ and $Y$ are bases of $F$, then by Theorem 2.10, $\pi(X)$ and $\pi(Y)$ are bases of the vector space $F/IF$ over $R/I$. By Theorem 2.7, $|\pi(X)| = |\pi(Y)|$. Since $\pi$ is injective on bases (Theorem 2.10), $|X| = |Y|$.'

# Thm 2.13: Subspace Dimension Properties
write_yaml "subspace-dimension-properties" "subspace-dimension-properties" "Dimension Properties of Subspaces" "子空间的维数性质" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.2" "Theorem 2.13"
write_tex "subspace-dimension-properties" 'Let $W$ be a subspace of a vector space $V$ over a division ring $D$.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $\dim_D W \leq \dim_D V$;
\item[(ii)] if $\dim_D W = \dim_D V$ and $\dim_D V$ is finite, then $W = V$;
\item[(iii)] $\dim_D V = \dim_D W + \dim_D(V/W)$.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "subspace-dimension-properties" "Theorem 2.13 collects the essential dimension formulas for vector spaces: the dimension of a subspace never exceeds that of the ambient space; equality of finite dimensions forces equality of spaces; and the dimension is additive over quotients. These facts are proved by extending a basis of $W$ to a basis of $V$ (Theorem 2.4) and showing the remaining basis elements descend to a basis of $V/W$."
write_proof "subspace-dimension-properties" "IV.2" "basis-extension" '(i) Let $Y$ be a basis of $W$. By Theorem 2.4 there is a basis $X$ of $V$ containing $Y$. Therefore $\dim_D W = |Y| \le |X| = \dim_D V$.

(ii) If $|Y| = |X|$ and $|X|$ is finite, then since $Y \subset X$ we must have $Y = X$, whence $W = V$.

(iii) Show that $U = \{x + W \mid x \in X - Y\}$ is a basis of $V/W$. If $v \in V$, then $v = \sum r_i y_i + \sum s_j x_j$, so $v + W = \sum s_j(x_j + W)$, hence $U$ spans $V/W$. Linear independence of $U$ follows from linear independence of $X$. Thus $\dim_D V = |X| = |Y| + |X - Y| = |Y| + |U| = \dim_D W + \dim_D(V/W)$.'

# Thm 2.16: Dimension Formula for Tower of Division Rings
write_yaml "dimension-formula-tower-of-division-rings" "dimension-formula-tower-of-division-rings" "Dimension Formula for a Tower of Division Rings" "除环塔的维数公式" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.2" "Theorem 2.16"
write_tex "dimension-formula-tower-of-division-rings" 'Let $R,S,T$ be division rings such that $R \subset S \subset T$. Then
\[
\dim_R T = (\dim_S T)(\dim_R S).
\]
Furthermore, $\dim_R T$ is finite if and only if $\dim_S T$ and $\dim_R S$ are finite.'
write_intro "dimension-formula-tower-of-division-rings" "This is the multiplicative formula for dimensions in a tower of division rings, generalizing the degree formula for field extensions. If $R \subset S \subset T$ are division rings, then a basis of $T$ over $R$ is obtained by multiplying a basis of $T$ over $S$ with a basis of $S$ over $R$, showing the dimension multiplies."
write_proof "dimension-formula-tower-of-division-rings" "IV.2" "basis-multiplication" 'Let $U$ be a basis of $T$ over $S$ and $V$ a basis of $S$ over $R$. Show $\{vu \mid v \in V, u \in U\}$ is a basis of $T$ over $R$. For spanning: any $t \in T$ can be written as $t = \sum s_i u_i$ with $s_i \in S$, and each $s_i = \sum r_{ij} v_j$, so $t = \sum \sum r_{ij} v_j u_i$. For linear independence: if $\sum \sum r_{ij}(v_j u_i) = 0$, let $s_i = \sum r_{ij} v_j \in S$. Then $\sum s_i u_i = 0$, so each $s_i = 0$ by linear independence of $U$, then each $r_{ij} = 0$ by linear independence of $V$. Thus $\dim_R T = |U||V| = (\dim_S T)(\dim_R S)$.'

