# Def 3.1: Projective Module
write_yaml "projective-module" "projective-module" "Projective Module" "投射模" "definition" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.3" "Definition 3.1"
write_tex "projective-module" 'An $R$-module $P$ is said to be \emph{projective} if given any diagram of $R$-module homomorphisms
\[
\begin{array}{ccc}
& & P \\
& & f \downarrow \\
A & \xrightarrow{g} & B \to 0
\end{array}
\]
with bottom row exact (that is, $g$ an epimorphism), there exists an $R$-module homomorphism $h : P \to A$ such that the diagram is commutative (that is, $gh = f$).'
write_intro "projective-module" "A module $P$ is projective if every homomorphism from $P$ to a quotient $B$ lifts to a homomorphism from $P$ to the original module $A$. This lifting property against epimorphisms is the categorical definition of a projective object. Free modules are the prototypical examples, but projective modules generalize free modules (e.g., direct summands of free modules)."

# Thm 3.2: Free Modules are Projective
write_yaml "free-modules-are-projective" "free-modules-are-projective" "Every Free Module is Projective" "每个自由模都是投射模" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.3" "Theorem 3.2"
write_tex "free-modules-are-projective" 'Every free module $F$ over a ring $R$ with identity is projective.'
write_intro "free-modules-are-projective" "Theorem 3.2 establishes that free modules satisfy the projective lifting property. Given a free module on a set $X$, any homomorphism $f: F \to B$ can be lifted to $A$ by choosing preimages of the generators $f(\iota(x))$ under the epimorphism $g$, then extending to $F$ via the universal property."
write_proof "free-modules-are-projective" "IV.3" "lifting-via-generators" 'Given $g: A \to B$ an epimorphism and $f: F \to B$ with $F$ free on $X$ ($\iota: X \to F$). For each $x \in X$, $f(\iota(x)) \in B$. Since $g$ is epi, there exists $a_x \in A$ with $g(a_x) = f(\iota(x))$. The map $X \to A$ given by $x \mapsto a_x$ induces an $R$-module homomorphism $h: F \to A$ such that $h(\iota(x)) = a_x$. Then $gh(\iota(x)) = g(a_x) = f(\iota(x))$, so $gh\iota = f\iota$. By uniqueness in Theorem 2.1(iv), $gh = f$.'

# Cor 3.3: Homomorphic Image of Projective
write_yaml "homomorphic-image-of-projective" "homomorphic-image-of-projective" "Every Module is a Homomorphic Image of a Projective Module" "每个模都是投射模的同态像" "corollary" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.3" "Corollary 3.3"
write_tex "homomorphic-image-of-projective" 'Every module $A$ over a ring $R$ is the homomorphic image of a projective $R$-module.'
write_intro "homomorphic-image-of-projective" "Corollary 3.3 follows immediately from Theorem 3.2 and Corollary 2.2: every module is a quotient of a free module, and free modules are projective. Thus projective modules serve as 'resolutions' of arbitrary modules."

# Thm 3.4: Projective Module Equivalent Conditions
write_yaml "projective-module-equivalent-conditions" "projective-module-equivalent-conditions" "Equivalent Conditions for Projective Modules" "投射模的等价条件" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.3" "Theorem 3.4"
write_tex "projective-module-equivalent-conditions" 'Let $R$ be a ring. The following conditions on an $R$-module $P$ are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $P$ is projective;
\item[(ii)] every short exact sequence $0 \to A \xrightarrow{f} B \xrightarrow{g} P \to 0$ is split exact (hence $B \cong A \oplus P$);
\item[(iii)] there is a free module $F$ and an $R$-module $K$ such that $F \cong K \oplus P$.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "projective-module-equivalent-conditions" "Theorem 3.4 gives two equivalent characterizations of projective modules beyond the definition. Condition (ii) states that any short exact sequence ending in $P$ splits, so $P$ is always a direct summand of any module mapping onto it. Condition (iii) says $P$ is projective if and only if it is a direct summand of a free module."
write_proof "projective-module-equivalent-conditions" "IV.3" "diagram-chase" '(i) $\Rightarrow$ (ii) Consider the diagram with $1_P: P \to P$ and the epimorphism $g: B \to P$. By projectivity, there is $h: P \to B$ with $gh = 1_P$, so the sequence splits by Theorem 1.18.

(ii) $\Rightarrow$ (iii) By Corollary 2.2, there is a free module $F$ and an epimorphism $F \to P$. Extend to a short exact sequence $0 \to K \to F \to P \to 0$, which splits by (ii), giving $F \cong K \oplus P$.

(iii) $\Rightarrow$ (i) Given $F \cong K \oplus P$ with $F$ free, consider the diagram with $f: P \to B$ and epimorphism $g: A \to B$. Compose with projection to get a map from $F$, lift by projectivity of $F$, then restrict via the injection $P \to F$ to get the required lift $h: P \to A$.'

# Prop 3.5: Direct Sum Projective
write_yaml "direct-sum-projective-iff-summands-projective" "direct-sum-projective-iff-summands-projective" "A Direct Sum is Projective iff Each Summand is Projective" "直和为投射模当且仅当每个直和项是投射模" "proposition" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.3" "Proposition 3.5"
write_tex "direct-sum-projective-iff-summands-projective" 'Let $R$ be a ring. A direct sum of $R$-modules $\sum_{i \in I} P_i$ is projective if and only if each $P_i$ is projective.'
write_intro "direct-sum-projective-iff-summands-projective" "Proposition 3.5 shows that projectivity is preserved under direct sums and inherited by summands. If the sum is projective, each $P_j$ is a direct summand (via applying Theorem 3.4(iii) to each factor). Conversely, if each $P_j$ is projective, one can lift maps coordinatewise using the coproduct universal property."
write_proof "direct-sum-projective-iff-summands-projective" "IV.3" "coordinatewise-lifting" '($\Rightarrow$) If $\sum P_i$ is projective, then it is a direct summand of a free module $F$ by Theorem 3.4. Replacing $\sum P_i$, $P_j$, and $F$ in the proof of (iii) $\Rightarrow$ (i) of Theorem 3.4 shows each $P_j$ is projective. ($\Leftarrow$) If each $P_j$ is projective, then for a diagram with epimorphism $g: A \to B$ and $f: \sum P_i \to B$, compose with each injection to get $f\iota_j: P_j \to B$. By projectivity, there exists $h_j: P_j \to A$ such that $gh_j = f\iota_j$. By Theorem 1.13, there is a unique $h: \sum P_i \to A$ with $h\iota_j = h_j$; then $gh = f$.'

# Def 3.6: Injective Module
write_yaml "injective-module" "injective-module" "Injective Module" "内射模" "definition" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.3" "Definition 3.6"
write_tex "injective-module" 'An $R$-module $J$ is said to be \emph{injective} if given any diagram of $R$-module homomorphisms
\[
\begin{array}{ccc}
0 \to A & \xrightarrow{g} & B \\
f \downarrow & & \\
J & &
\end{array}
\]
with top row exact (that is, $g$ a monomorphism), there exists an $R$-module homomorphism $h : B \to J$ such that the diagram is commutative (that is, $hg = f$).'
write_intro "injective-module" "An injective module is the dual notion to a projective module: instead of lifting maps against epimorphisms, injective modules extend maps along monomorphisms. Every homomorphism from a submodule $A$ into $J$ can be extended to a homomorphism from the larger module $B$ into $J$. Injective modules play a fundamental role in homological algebra."

# Prop 3.7: Direct Product Injective
write_yaml "direct-product-injective-iff-factors-injective" "direct-product-injective-iff-factors-injective" "A Direct Product is Injective iff Each Factor is Injective" "直积为内射模当且仅当每个因子是内射模" "proposition" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.3" "Proposition 3.7"
write_tex "direct-product-injective-iff-factors-injective" 'A direct product of $R$-modules $\prod_{i \in I} J_i$ is injective if and only if $J_i$ is injective for every $i \in I$.'
write_intro "direct-product-injective-iff-factors-injective" "Proposition 3.7 is the dual of Proposition 3.5. The direct product of modules is injective precisely when each factor is injective. The proof is dual to that of Proposition 3.5: extend maps coordinatewise using the product universal property."

# Lemma 3.8: Injective Extension from Left Ideals
write_yaml "injective-extension-from-left-ideals" "injective-extension-from-left-ideals" "Injective Module Characterization via Left Ideals" "通过左理想刻画内射模" "lemma" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.3" "Lemma 3.8"
write_tex "injective-extension-from-left-ideals" 'Let $R$ be a ring with identity. A unitary $R$-module $J$ is injective if and only if for every left ideal $L$ of $R$, any $R$-module homomorphism $L \to J$ may be extended to an $R$-module homomorphism $R \to J$.'
write_intro "injective-extension-from-left-ideals" "Lemma 3.8 is Baer'\''s criterion for injectivity: to check that a module is injective, it suffices to verify the extension property for maps from left ideals of $R$ into $J$. This reduces the verification from arbitrary monomorphisms to the much smaller class of inclusions of left ideals. The proof uses Zorn'\''s Lemma to extend a maximal partial extension to the whole module."
write_proof "injective-extension-from-left-ideals" "IV.3" "zorns-lemma-extension" 'If $J$ is injective, the extension property holds by definition. Conversely, suppose $J$ has the extension property for left ideals and we have a diagram with $g: A \to B$ a monomorphism and $f: A \to J$. Let $\mathcal{S}$ be the set of all $R$-module homomorphisms $h: C \to J$ where $\operatorname{Im} g \subset C \subset B$, partially ordered by extension. $\mathcal{S}$ is nonempty (contains $fg^{-1}$). Zorn'\''s Lemma gives a maximal element $h: H \to J$. If $H \neq B$, pick $b \in B - H$. Then $L = \{r \in R \mid rb \in H\}$ is a left ideal. The map $L \to J$, $r \mapsto h(rb)$, extends to $R \to J$ by hypothesis, yielding $c = k(1_R)$. Define $\bar{h}: H + Rb \to J$ by $a + rb \mapsto h(a) + rc$, which extends $h$ properly, contradicting maximality. Hence $H = B$.'

# Lemma 3.9: Injective Z-modules are Divisible
write_yaml "injective-z-modules-are-divisible" "injective-z-modules-are-divisible" "Injective Z-Modules are Divisible Abelian Groups" "内射Z-模是可除阿贝尔群" "lemma" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.3" "Lemma 3.9"
write_tex "injective-z-modules-are-divisible" 'A unitary $\mathbb{Z}$-module $D$ is injective if and only if $D$ is a divisible abelian group (that is, for every $d \in D$ and nonzero $n \in \mathbb{Z}$, there exists $x \in D$ such that $nx = d$).'
write_intro "injective-z-modules-are-divisible" "Lemma 3.9 characterizes injective abelian groups as precisely the divisible groups. This connects the ring-theoretic notion of injectivity to the classical group-theoretic notion of divisibility. The proof uses Lemma 3.8: the only left ideals of $\mathbb{Z}$ are principal, and extending a map $\langle n \rangle \to D$ is equivalent to solving $nx = f(n)$ in $D$."
write_proof "injective-z-modules-are-divisible" "IV.3" "baer-criterion" '($\Rightarrow$) If $D$ is injective and $d \in D$, $n \neq 0$, define $f: \langle n \rangle \to D$ by $f(n) = d$. The map $n \mapsto nd$ is a homomorphism since $\langle n \rangle \cong \mathbb{Z}$. By Lemma 3.8, extend to $h: \mathbb{Z} \to D$. If $x = h(1)$, then $nx = nh(1) = h(n) = f(n) = d$, so $D$ is divisible.

($\Leftarrow$) If $D$ is divisible and $f: \langle n \rangle \to D$, there exists $x \in D$ with $nx = f(n)$. Define $h: \mathbb{Z} \to D$ by $1 \mapsto x$, which extends $f$. By Lemma 3.8, $D$ is injective.'

# Lemma 3.10: Embedding in Divisible Abelian Group
write_yaml "embedding-in-divisible-abelian-group" "embedding-in-divisible-abelian-group" "Every Abelian Group Can Be Embedded in a Divisible Group" "每个阿贝尔群可嵌入可除群" "lemma" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.3" "Lemma 3.10"
write_tex "embedding-in-divisible-abelian-group" 'Every abelian group $A$ may be embedded in a divisible abelian group.'
write_intro "embedding-in-divisible-abelian-group" "Lemma 3.10 is a key construction: every abelian group can be embedded as a subgroup of a divisible (hence injective) abelian group. The proof writes $A \cong F/K$ with $F$ free abelian, embeds $F$ in a direct sum $D$ of copies of $\mathbb{Q}$, and notes that the quotient $D/f(K)$ remains divisible."
write_proof "embedding-in-divisible-abelian-group" "IV.3" "free-resolution-embedding" 'By Theorem II.1.4 there is a free $\mathbb{Z}$-module $F$ and an epimorphism $F \to A$ with kernel $K$, so $F/K \cong A$. Since $F$ is a direct sum of copies of $\mathbb{Z}$ (Theorem II.1.1) and $\mathbb{Z} \subset \mathbb{Q}$, $F$ may be embedded in a direct sum $D$ of copies of $\mathbb{Q}$. $D$ is divisible by Proposition 3.7 and Lemma 3.9. If $f: F \to D$ is the embedding, then $f$ induces $F/K \cong f(F)/f(K) \subset D/f(K)$. Thus $A \cong F/K \cong f(F)/f(K) \subset D/f(K)$, and $D/f(K)$ is divisible as the homomorphic image of a divisible group.'

# Lemma 3.11: Extension via Hom_Z(R,J)
write_yaml "extension-from-left-ideals-via-hom" "extension-from-left-ideals-via-hom" "Extension from Left Ideals via Hom_Z(R,J)" "通过Hom_Z(R,J)从左理想扩张" "lemma" "module-theory" "advanced" "IV.3" "Lemma 3.11"
write_tex "extension-from-left-ideals-via-hom" 'If $R$ is a ring with identity and $J$ is a divisible abelian group, then $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,J)$ is an injective left $R$-module.'
write_intro "extension-from-left-ideals-via-hom" "Lemma 3.11 constructs an important injective module: if $J$ is any injective abelian group (divisible group), then $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,J)$ with the $R$-module structure $(rf)(x) = f(xr)$ is an injective $R$-module. This is the coinduction functor from $\mathbb{Z}$-modules to $R$-modules, preserving injectivity."
write_proof "extension-from-left-ideals-via-hom" "IV.3" "adjunction-argument" 'Let $L$ be a left ideal of $R$ and $f: L \to \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,J)$ an $R$-module homomorphism. Define $g: L \to J$ by $g(r) = f(r)(1_R)$. Since $J$ is divisible (hence injective over $\mathbb{Z}$), there is a group homomorphism $\bar{g}: R \to J$ extending $g$. Define $h: R \to \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,J)$ by $h(r)(x) = \bar{g}(xr)$. Verify $h$ is an $R$-module homomorphism extending $f$. By Lemma 3.8, $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,J)$ is injective.'

# Prop 3.12: Embedding in Injective Module
write_yaml "embedding-in-injective-module" "embedding-in-injective-module" "Every Module Can Be Embedded in an Injective Module" "每个模可嵌入内射模" "proposition" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.3" "Proposition 3.12"
write_tex "embedding-in-injective-module" 'Every unitary module $A$ over a ring $R$ with identity may be embedded in an injective $R$-module.'
write_intro "embedding-in-injective-module" "Proposition 3.12 is the dual of Corollary 3.3: every module can be embedded in an injective module. The proof uses Lemma 3.10 to embed the underlying abelian group in a divisible group $J$, then maps $A$ into $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,J)$, which is injective by Lemma 3.11."
write_proof "embedding-in-injective-module" "IV.3" "coinduction" 'Since $A$ is an abelian group, there is a divisible group $J$ and a group monomorphism $f: A \to J$ (Lemma 3.10). The map $\bar{f}: \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,A) \to \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,J)$ given by $g \mapsto fg$ is a monomorphism. Compose with the natural $R$-module monomorphism $A \to \operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,A)$ (given by $a \mapsto \phi_a$ where $\phi_a(r) = ra$) to embed $A$ in $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathbb{Z}}(R,J)$, which is injective by Lemma 3.11.'

# Prop 3.13: Injective Module Equivalent Conditions
write_yaml "injective-module-equivalent-conditions" "injective-module-equivalent-conditions" "Equivalent Conditions for Injective Modules" "内射模的等价条件" "proposition" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.3" "Proposition 3.13"
write_tex "injective-module-equivalent-conditions" 'The following conditions on a unitary module $J$ over a ring $R$ with identity are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $J$ is injective;
\item[(ii)] every short exact sequence $0 \to J \xrightarrow{f} B \xrightarrow{g} C \to 0$ is split exact (hence $B \cong J \oplus C$);
\item[(iii)] $J$ is a direct summand of any module $B$ containing $J$ as a submodule.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "injective-module-equivalent-conditions" "Proposition 3.13 is the dual of Theorem 3.4. An injective module is characterized by the property that it is always a direct summand of any module containing it (condition (iii)), or equivalently that any short exact sequence beginning with $J$ splits (condition (ii))."
write_proof "injective-module-equivalent-conditions" "IV.3" "dual-diagram-chase" '(i) $\Rightarrow$ (ii) Given $f: J \to B$ mono (exact sequence) and $1_J: J \to J$, injectivity gives $k: B \to J$ with $kf = 1_J$, so the sequence splits.

(ii) $\Rightarrow$ (iii) The sequence $0 \to J \to B \to B/J \to 0$ is exact; by (ii) it splits, so $B \cong J \oplus (B/J)$.

(iii) $\Rightarrow$ (i) By Proposition 3.12, $J$ is a submodule of an injective module $Q$. By (iii), $J$ is a direct summand of $Q$. By Proposition 3.7 (product-injective iff each factor), $J$ is injective.'

