# Thm 4.2: Hom Left Exactness (Covariant)
write_yaml "hom-left-exactness-covariant" "hom-left-exactness-covariant" "Left Exactness of Hom in the Covariant Argument" "Hom在协变变元的左正合性" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.4" "Theorem 4.2"
write_tex "hom-left-exactness-covariant" 'Let $R$ be a ring. $0 \to A \xrightarrow{\varphi} B \xrightarrow{\psi} C$ is an exact sequence of $R$-modules if and only if for every $R$-module $D$,
\[
0 \to \operatorname{Hom}_R(D, A) \xrightarrow{\bar{\varphi}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(D, B) \xrightarrow{\bar{\psi}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(D, C)
\]
is an exact sequence of abelian groups (where $\bar{\varphi}(f) = \varphi f$ and $\bar{\psi}(g) = \psi g$).'
write_intro "hom-left-exactness-covariant" "Theorem 4.2 establishes that the Hom functor is left exact in the second variable. It preserves monomorphisms and kernels, but not necessarily epimorphisms. This left exactness is fundamental to homological algebra: a short exact sequence $0 \to A \to B \to C \to 0$ induces an exact sequence $0 \to \operatorname{Hom}(D,A) \to \operatorname{Hom}(D,B) \to \operatorname{Hom}(D,C)$, which in general does not continue with $\to 0$."
write_proof "hom-left-exactness-covariant" "IV.4" "kernel-chase" '($\Rightarrow$) (i) $\operatorname{Ker} \bar{\varphi} = 0$: if $\varphi f = 0$, then $\varphi(f(x)) = 0$ for all $x$. Since $\varphi$ is mono, $f(x) = 0$, so $f = 0$. (ii) $\operatorname{Im} \bar{\varphi} \subset \operatorname{Ker} \bar{\psi}$: $\psi \varphi = 0$ (by exactness), so $\bar{\psi}\bar{\varphi}(f) = \psi \varphi f = 0$. (iii) $\operatorname{Ker} \bar{\psi} \subset \operatorname{Im} \bar{\varphi}$: if $\psi g = 0$, then $\operatorname{Im} g \subset \operatorname{Ker} \psi = \operatorname{Im} \varphi$. Since $\varphi$ is mono, for each $d \in D$ there is a unique $a \in A$ with $g(d) = \varphi(a)$. Define $f(d) = a$; verify $f$ is an $R$-module homomorphism and $\bar{\varphi}(f) = g$.

($\Leftarrow$) Given exactness of Hom for all $D$, take $D = \operatorname{Ker} \varphi$ to show $\varphi$ is mono, and $D = B/\operatorname{Im} \varphi$ to show $\operatorname{Im} \varphi = \operatorname{Ker} \psi$.'

# Thm 4.3: Hom Left Exactness (Contravariant)
write_yaml "hom-left-exactness-contravariant" "hom-left-exactness-contravariant" "Left Exactness of Hom in the Contravariant Argument" "Hom在反变变元的左正合性" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.4" "Theorem 4.3"
write_tex "hom-left-exactness-contravariant" 'Let $R$ be a ring. $A \xrightarrow{\theta} B \xrightarrow{\zeta} C \to 0$ is an exact sequence of $R$-modules if and only if for every $R$-module $D$,
\[
0 \to \operatorname{Hom}_R(C, D) \xrightarrow{\bar{\zeta}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(B, D) \xrightarrow{\bar{\theta}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(A, D)
\]
is an exact sequence of abelian groups (where $\bar{\zeta}(f) = f\zeta$ and $\bar{\theta}(g) = g\theta$).'
write_intro "hom-left-exactness-contravariant" "Theorem 4.3 is the dual of Theorem 4.2. The contravariant Hom functor $\operatorname{Hom}_R(-, D)$ sends an exact sequence $A \to B \to C \to 0$ to an exact sequence $0 \to \operatorname{Hom}(C,D) \to \operatorname{Hom}(B,D) \to \operatorname{Hom}(A,D)$. It preserves cokernels (reverses epimorphisms to monomorphisms) but not necessarily kernels."
write_proof "hom-left-exactness-contravariant" "IV.4" "dual-kernel-chase" '($\Rightarrow$) (i) $\operatorname{Ker} \bar{\zeta} = 0$: if $f\zeta = 0$, then $f(\zeta(b)) = 0$ for all $b$. Since $\zeta$ is epi, $f(c) = 0$ for all $c \in C$, so $f = 0$. (ii) $\operatorname{Im} \bar{\zeta} \subset \operatorname{Ker} \bar{\theta}$: $\zeta \theta = 0$ implies $\bar{\theta}\bar{\zeta}(f) = f\zeta\theta = 0$. (iii) $\operatorname{Ker} \bar{\theta} \subset \operatorname{Im} \bar{\zeta}$: if $g\theta = 0$, then $g$ vanishes on $\operatorname{Im} \theta = \operatorname{Ker} \zeta$, so $g$ factors uniquely through $C$.

($\Leftarrow$) Similar to Theorem 4.2, using suitable choices of $D$.'

# Prop 4.4: Split Exact Preserved by Hom
write_yaml "split-exact-preserved-by-hom" "split-exact-preserved-by-hom" "Split Exact Sequences are Preserved by Hom" "Hom保持分裂正合列" "proposition" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.4" "Proposition 4.4"
write_tex "split-exact-preserved-by-hom" 'The following conditions on modules over a ring $R$ are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $0 \to A \xrightarrow{\varphi} B \xrightarrow{\psi} C \to 0$ is a split exact sequence of $R$-modules;
\item[(ii)] $0 \to \operatorname{Hom}_R(D,A) \xrightarrow{\bar{\varphi}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(D,B) \xrightarrow{\bar{\psi}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(D,C) \to 0$ is a split exact sequence of abelian groups for every $R$-module $D$;
\item[(iii)] $0 \to \operatorname{Hom}_R(C,D) \xrightarrow{\bar{\psi}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(B,D) \xrightarrow{\bar{\varphi}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(A,D) \to 0$ is a split exact sequence of abelian groups for every $R$-module $D$.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "split-exact-preserved-by-hom" "Proposition 4.4 states that split exact sequences are preserved by both the covariant and contravariant Hom functors. While Hom is only left exact in general, split exactness guarantees the extended exact sequence ending in $\to 0$ is also exact. This is because split epimorphisms (those with a section) remain epimorphisms after applying Hom."
write_proof "split-exact-preserved-by-hom" "IV.4" "section-retraction-transfer" '(i) $\Rightarrow$ (iii) By Theorem 1.18, there is $h: C \to B$ with $\psi h = 1_C$ and $k: B \to A$ with $k\varphi = 1_A$. Then $\bar{h}: \operatorname{Hom}(B,D) \to \operatorname{Hom}(C,D)$ (precomposition by $h$) satisfies $\bar{\psi}\bar{h} = 1$, so $\bar{\psi}$ is a split epi. Similarly, $\bar{k}: \operatorname{Hom}(A,D) \to \operatorname{Hom}(B,D)$ gives a section for $\bar{\varphi}$. This yields the split exact sequence in (iii). The other implications are proved similarly using the splitting maps.'

# Thm 4.5: Projective Characterization via Hom
write_yaml "projective-characterization-via-hom" "projective-characterization-via-hom" "Projective Module Characterization via Hom" "通过Hom刻画投射模" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.4" "Theorem 4.5"
write_tex "projective-characterization-via-hom" 'The following conditions on a module $P$ over a ring $R$ are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $P$ is projective;
\item[(ii)] if $\psi : B \to C$ is any $R$-module epimorphism, then $\bar{\psi} : \operatorname{Hom}_R(P, B) \to \operatorname{Hom}_R(P, C)$ is an epimorphism of abelian groups;
\item[(iii)] if $0 \to A \xrightarrow{\varphi} B \xrightarrow{\psi} C \to 0$ is any short exact sequence of $R$-modules, then $0 \to \operatorname{Hom}_R(P, A) \xrightarrow{\bar{\varphi}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(P, B) \xrightarrow{\bar{\psi}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(P, C) \to 0$ is an exact sequence of abelian groups.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "projective-characterization-via-hom" "Theorem 4.5 characterizes projective modules in terms of the Hom functor: $P$ is projective precisely when $\operatorname{Hom}_R(P, -)$ preserves epimorphisms, or equivalently when it preserves short exact sequences (not just left exactness). This is a fundamental bridge between the categorical definition of projectivity and homological algebra."
write_proof "projective-characterization-via-hom" "IV.4" "lifting-equivalence" '(i) $\Rightarrow$ (ii) Given $f \in \operatorname{Hom}_R(P, C)$, by projectivity there exists $g: P \to B$ with $\psi g = f$, so $\bar{\psi}(g) = \psi g = f$, hence $\bar{\psi}$ is surjective.

(ii) $\Rightarrow$ (iii) Combine (ii) with Theorem 4.2.

(iii) $\Rightarrow$ (i) Given an epimorphism $\psi: B \to C$, let $A = \operatorname{Ker} \psi$ and apply (iii) to the short exact sequence $0 \to A \to B \to C \to 0$. The surjectivity of $\bar{\psi}$ in the resulting exact sequence gives the required lifting property.'

# Prop 4.6: Injective Characterization via Hom
write_yaml "injective-characterization-via-hom" "injective-characterization-via-hom" "Injective Module Characterization via Hom" "通过Hom刻画内射模" "proposition" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.4" "Proposition 4.6"
write_tex "injective-characterization-via-hom" 'The following conditions on a module $J$ over a ring $R$ are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $J$ is injective;
\item[(ii)] if $\theta : A \to B$ is any $R$-module monomorphism, then $\bar{\theta} : \operatorname{Hom}_R(B, J) \to \operatorname{Hom}_R(A, J)$ is an epimorphism of abelian groups;
\item[(iii)] if $0 \to A \xrightarrow{\theta} B \xrightarrow{\xi} C \to 0$ is any short exact sequence of $R$-modules, then $0 \to \operatorname{Hom}_R(C, J) \xrightarrow{\bar{\xi}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(B, J) \xrightarrow{\bar{\theta}} \operatorname{Hom}_R(A, J) \to 0$ is an exact sequence of abelian groups.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "injective-characterization-via-hom" "Proposition 4.6 is the dual of Theorem 4.5. $J$ is injective precisely when $\operatorname{Hom}_R(-, J)$ sends monomorphisms to epimorphisms, or equivalently when it preserves short exact sequences (converting them to short exact sequences of abelian groups). The proof is dual to that of Theorem 4.5."

# Thm 4.7: Hom Isomorphisms for Sum and Product
write_yaml "hom-isomorphisms-for-sum-and-product" "hom-isomorphisms-for-sum-and-product" "Hom Isomorphisms for Direct Sums and Products" "Hom关于直和与直积的同构" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.4" "Theorem 4.7"
write_tex "hom-isomorphisms-for-sum-and-product" 'Let $A, B, \{A_i \mid i \in I\}$ and $\{B_j \mid j \in J\}$ be modules over a ring $R$. Then there are isomorphisms of abelian groups:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $\operatorname{Hom}_R(\sum_{i \in I} A_i, B) \cong \prod_{i \in I} \operatorname{Hom}_R(A_i, B)$;
\item[(ii)] $\operatorname{Hom}_R(A, \prod_{j \in J} B_j) \cong \prod_{j \in J} \operatorname{Hom}_R(A, B_j)$.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "hom-isomorphisms-for-sum-and-product" "Theorem 4.7 relates Hom to categorical limits: Hom from a direct sum to a module is isomorphic to the product of the individual Homs, and Hom into a direct product is isomorphic to the product of the individual Homs. These isomorphisms are given by restricting to summands/factors and are fundamental adjunction relations."

# Thm 4.8: Hom as Bimodule
write_yaml "hom-as-bimodule" "hom-as-bimodule" "The Hom-Set as a Bimodule" "Hom集作为双模" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.4" "Theorem 4.8"
write_tex "hom-as-bimodule" 'Let $R$ and $S$ be rings and let ${}_R A_S$, ${}_R B$, ${}_R C_S$, ${}_R D$ be (bi)modules as indicated.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $\operatorname{Hom}_R(A,B)$ is a right $S$-module, with the action of $S$ given by $(fs)(a) = (f(a))s$ ($s \in S$, $a \in A$, $f \in \operatorname{Hom}_R(A,B))$.
\item[(ii)] If $\varphi : A \to A'\'$ is a homomorphism of left $R$-modules, then the induced map $\bar{\varphi} : \operatorname{Hom}_R(A'\',B) \to \operatorname{Hom}_R(A,B)$ is a homomorphism of right $S$-modules.
\item[(iii)] $\operatorname{Hom}_R(C,D)$ is a left $S$-module, with the action of $S$ given by $(sg)(c) = g(cs)$ ($s \in S$, $c \in C$, $g \in \operatorname{Hom}_R(C,D))$.
\item[(iv)] If $\psi : D \to D'\'$ is a homomorphism of left $R$-modules, then $\bar{\psi} : \operatorname{Hom}_R(C,D) \to \operatorname{Hom}_R(C,D'\'')$ is a homomorphism of left $S$-modules.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "hom-as-bimodule" "When modules carry bimodule structures, the Hom sets inherit module structures over the second ring. If $A$ is an $R$-$S$ bimodule, then $\operatorname{Hom}_R(A,B)$ is a right $S$-module. If $C$ is an $R$-$S$ bimodule, then $\operatorname{Hom}_R(C,D)$ is a left $S$-module. The induced maps are module homomorphisms over $S$."

# Thm 4.10: Dual Module Properties
write_yaml "dual-module-properties" "dual-module-properties" "Properties of the Dual Module" "对偶模的性质" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.4" "Theorem 4.10"
write_tex "dual-module-properties" 'Let $A, B$ and $C$ be left modules over a ring $R$ and let $A^* = \operatorname{Hom}_R(A,R)$ (the dual module).
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] If $\varphi : A \to C$ is a homomorphism of left $R$-modules, then the induced map $\bar{\varphi} : C^* = \operatorname{Hom}_R(C,R) \to \operatorname{Hom}_R(A,R) = A^*$ is a homomorphism of right $R$-modules.
\item[(ii)] There is an $R$-module isomorphism $(A \oplus C)^* \cong A^* \oplus C^*$.
\item[(iii)] If $R$ is a division ring and $0 \to A \xrightarrow{\theta} B \xrightarrow{\zeta} C \to 0$ is a short exact sequence of left vector spaces, then $0 \to C^* \xrightarrow{\bar{\zeta}} B^* \xrightarrow{\bar{\theta}} A^* \to 0$ is a short exact sequence of right vector spaces.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "dual-module-properties" "The dual module $A^* = \operatorname{Hom}_R(A,R)$ enjoys several important properties. Dualization is a contravariant functor sending left modules to right modules. It respects direct sums (ii). Over a division ring (the vector space case), dualization preserves short exact sequences (iii), a consequence of the fact that vector spaces are both projective and injective."

# Thm 4.11: Dual of a Free Module
write_yaml "dual-of-free-module" "dual-of-free-module" "The Dual of a Free Module" "自由模的对偶" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.4" "Theorem 4.11"
write_tex "dual-of-free-module" 'Let $F$ be a free left $R$-module with finite basis $X = \{x_1, \ldots, x_n\}$ over a ring $R$ with identity. For each $x \in X$, define $f_x : F \to R$ by $f_x(\sum r_i x_i) = r_x$ (the coefficient of $x$). Then $\{f_x \mid x \in X\}$ is a basis of the right $R$-module $F^* = \operatorname{Hom}_R(F,R)$. Hence $F^*$ is a free right $R$-module of the same rank as $F$.'
write_intro "dual-of-free-module" "Theorem 4.11 shows that the dual of a finitely generated free module is again free, with the 'coordinate functionals' forming a basis. This generalizes the notion of the dual basis in linear algebra. The proof verifies both linear independence and the spanning property of the $f_x$."
write_proof "dual-of-free-module" "IV.4" "coordinate-functional-basis" 'Given $f \in F^*$, let $s_i = f(x_i) \in R$. Then for any $u = \sum r_i x_i \in F$, $\langle u, f \rangle = f(\sum r_i x_i) = \sum r_i f(x_i) = \sum r_i s_i$. On the other hand, $\langle u, \sum f_i s_i \rangle = \sum \langle \sum r_j x_j, f_i \rangle s_i = \sum \sum r_j \delta_{ji} s_i = \sum r_i s_i$. Thus $f = \sum f_i s_i$, showing $\{f_i\}$ generates $F^*$. Linear independence: if $\sum f_i r_i = 0$, evaluate at $x_j$ to get $r_j = 0$. Hence $\{f_x\}$ is a basis.'

# Thm 4.12: Double Dual and Reflexive Modules
write_yaml "double-dual-and-reflexive-modules" "double-dual-and-reflexive-modules" "The Double Dual and Reflexive Modules" "双重对偶与自反模" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.4" "Theorem 4.12"
write_tex "double-dual-and-reflexive-modules" 'Let $A$ be a left module over a ring $R$.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] There is an $R$-module homomorphism $\theta : A \to A^{**}$.
\item[(ii)] If $R$ has an identity and $A$ is free, then $\theta$ is a monomorphism.
\item[(iii)] If $R$ has an identity and $A$ is free with a finite basis, then $\theta$ is an isomorphism.
\end{enumerate}
A module $A$ such that $\theta : A \to A^{**}$ is an isomorphism is said to be \emph{reflexive}.'
write_intro "double-dual-and-reflexive-modules" "There is a natural map $\theta: A \to A^{**}$ from any module to its double dual, defined by evaluation: $\theta(a)(f) = f(a)$. For free modules, this map is injective; for finitely generated free modules, it is an isomorphism -- such modules are called reflexive. This generalizes the fact from linear algebra that a finite-dimensional vector space is naturally isomorphic to its double dual."
write_proof "double-dual-and-reflexive-modules" "IV.4" "evaluation-map" '(i) Define $\theta: A \to A^{**}$ by $\theta(a)(f) = f(a)$ for $a \in A$, $f \in A^*$. Verify $\theta$ is an $R$-module homomorphism.

(ii) If $A$ is free with basis $X$, let $a \in \operatorname{Ker} \theta$. Write $a = \sum r_i x_i$. Then $\theta(a)(f_x) = f_x(a) = r_x = 0$ for each $x \in X$, so $a = 0$. Hence $\theta$ is mono.

(iii) If the basis $X = \{x_1,\ldots,x_n\}$ is finite, then using the dual basis $\{f_i\}$ of $A^*$ and the double dual basis, one shows $\theta$ is surjective by constructing preimages for each basis element of $A^{**}$.'

