# Def 5.1: Tensor Product
write_yaml "tensor-product" "tensor-product" "Tensor Product of Modules" "模的张量积" "definition" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.5" "Definition 5.1"
write_tex "tensor-product" 'Let $A$ be a right module and $B$ a left module over a ring $R$. Let $F$ be the free abelian group on the set $A \times B$. Let $K$ be the subgroup of $F$ generated by all elements of the following forms (for all $a,a\'\' \in A; b,b\'\' \in B; r \in R$):
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $(a + a\'\',b) - (a,b) - (a\'\',b)$;
\item[(ii)] $(a,b + b\'\') - (a,b) - (a,b\'\'')$;
\item[(iii)] $(ar,b) - (a,rb)$.
\end{enumerate}
The quotient group $F/K$ is called the \emph{tensor product} of $A$ and $B$; it is denoted $A \otimes_R B$ (or simply $A \otimes B$ if $R = \mathbb{Z}$). The coset $(a,b) + K$ is denoted $a \otimes b$.'
write_intro "tensor-product" "The tensor product $A \otimes_R B$ is the universal bilinear (more precisely, middle linear) construction on the product $A \times B$. It is the quotient of the free abelian group on $A \times B$ by the relations enforcing bilinearity and the balanced condition $(ar) \otimes b = a \otimes (rb)$. The tensor product is generated by elementary tensors $a \otimes b$, though not every element is of this simple form."

# Thm 5.2: Tensor Product Universal Property
write_yaml "tensor-product-universal-property" "tensor-product-universal-property" "Universal Property of the Tensor Product" "张量积的万有性质" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.5" "Theorem 5.2"
write_tex "tensor-product-universal-property" 'Let $A_R$ and ${}_R B$ be modules over a ring $R$, and let $C$ be an abelian group. If $g : A \times B \to C$ is a middle linear map, then there exists a unique group homomorphism $\bar{g} : A \otimes_R B \to C$ such that $\bar{g}i = g$, where $i : A \times B \to A \otimes_R B$ is the canonical middle linear map ($i(a,b) = a \otimes b$). $A \otimes_R B$ is uniquely determined up to isomorphism by this property.'
write_intro "tensor-product-universal-property" "Theorem 5.2 is the fundamental universal property of the tensor product: any middle linear map from $A \times B$ to an abelian group $C$ factors uniquely through the tensor product. This characterizes the tensor product up to unique isomorphism and is the basis for all subsequent properties."
write_proof "tensor-product-universal-property" "IV.5" "universal-property" 'Let $F$ be the free abelian group on $A \times B$ and $K$ the subgroup described in Definition 5.1. Since $F$ is free, the assignment $(a,b) \mapsto g(a,b) \in C$ determines a unique homomorphism $g_1: F \to C$. Since $g$ is middle linear, $g_1$ maps every generator of $K$ to 0, so $K \subset \operatorname{Ker} g_1$. By Theorem 1.7, $g_1$ induces a homomorphism $\bar{g}: F/K \to C$ with $\bar{g}[(a,b) + K] = g(a,b)$. But $F/K = A \otimes_R B$ and $(a,b) + K = a \otimes b$, so $\bar{g}(a \otimes b) = g(a,b)$. Uniqueness follows because the elementary tensors generate $A \otimes_R B$.'

# Thm 5.4: Tensor Product Right Exactness
write_yaml "tensor-product-right-exactness" "tensor-product-right-exactness" "Right Exactness of the Tensor Product" "张量积的右正合性" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.5" "Theorem 5.4"
write_tex "tensor-product-right-exactness" 'Let $R$ be a ring. If $A \xrightarrow{f} B \xrightarrow{g} C \to 0$ is an exact sequence of left $R$-modules, then for every right $R$-module $D$,
\[
D \otimes_R A \xrightarrow{1_D \otimes f} D \otimes_R B \xrightarrow{1_D \otimes g} D \otimes_R C \to 0
\]
is an exact sequence of abelian groups. An analogous statement holds for an exact sequence in the first variable.'
write_intro "tensor-product-right-exactness" "The tensor product is right exact: it preserves cokernels and epimorphisms, but not necessarily kernels. Given an exact sequence $A \to B \to C \to 0$, tensoring with $D$ yields $D \otimes A \to D \otimes B \to D \otimes C \to 0$ exact. This is the dual of the left exactness of Hom and is equally fundamental to homological algebra."
write_proof "tensor-product-right-exactness" "IV.5" "universal-property-chase" '(i) $\operatorname{Im}(1_D \otimes g) = D \otimes_R C$: every generator $d \otimes c$ equals $(1_D \otimes g)(d \otimes b)$ for some $b \in B$ since $g$ is epi. (ii) $\operatorname{Im}(1_D \otimes f) \subset \operatorname{Ker}(1_D \otimes g)$: $gf = 0$ implies $(1_D \otimes g)(1_D \otimes f) = 1_D \otimes gf = 0$. (iii) $\operatorname{Ker}(1_D \otimes g) \subset \operatorname{Im}(1_D \otimes f)$: let $\pi: D \otimes B \to (D \otimes B)/\operatorname{Im}(1_D \otimes f)$. By (ii) there is $\alpha: (D \otimes B)/\operatorname{Im}(1_D \otimes f) \to D \otimes C$. Construct an inverse to $\alpha$ using the universal property of tensor product, showing $\alpha$ is an isomorphism, hence $\operatorname{Ker}(1_D \otimes g) = \operatorname{Im}(1_D \otimes f)$.'

# Thm 5.5: Tensor Product as Bimodule
write_yaml "tensor-product-as-bimodule" "tensor-product-as-bimodule" "Tensor Product as a Bimodule" "张量积作为双模" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.5" "Theorem 5.5"
write_tex "tensor-product-as-bimodule" 'Let $R$, $S$ be rings. If $A$ is a left $S$-right $R$ bimodule and $B$ is a left $R$-module, then $A \otimes_R B$ is a left $S$-module with $s(a \otimes b) = (sa) \otimes b$ for all $s \in S$, $a \in A$, $b \in B$. Similarly, if $A$ is a right $R$-module and $B$ is a left $R$-right $S$ bimodule, then $A \otimes_R B$ is a right $S$-module.'
write_intro "tensor-product-as-bimodule" "When one of the factors carries an additional bimodule structure, the tensor product inherits a module structure over the extra ring. This is crucial for extension and restriction of scalars. For example, if $R$ is commutative, $A \otimes_R B$ is an $R$-$R$ bimodule with $r(a \otimes b) = (ra) \otimes b = a \otimes (rb)$."

# Thm 5.6: Bilinear Maps (Commutative Case)
write_yaml "tensor-product-bilinear-maps-commutative" "tensor-product-bilinear-maps-commutative" "Universal Property for Bilinear Maps over Commutative Rings" "交换环上双线性映射的万有性质" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.5" "Theorem 5.6"
write_tex "tensor-product-bilinear-maps-commutative" 'Let $A, B, C$ be modules over a commutative ring $R$. If $f: A \times B \to C$ is an $R$-bilinear map, then there exists a unique $R$-module homomorphism $\bar{f}: A \otimes_R B \to C$ such that $\bar{f}(a \otimes b) = f(a,b)$. The tensor product $A \otimes_R B$ is uniquely determined up to $R$-module isomorphism by this property.'
write_intro "tensor-product-bilinear-maps-commutative" "Over a commutative ring, the tensor product satisfies a stronger universal property: $R$-bilinear maps from $A \times B$ correspond uniquely to $R$-module homomorphisms from $A \otimes_R B$. The tensor product itself is an $R$-module, and the universal map is $R$-bilinear, not just middle linear."

# Thm 5.7: Tensor with Ring
write_yaml "tensor-with-ring-isomorphism" "tensor-with-ring-isomorphism" "Tensoring with the Base Ring" "与基环作张量积" "theorem" "module-theory" "basic" "IV.5" "Theorem 5.7"
write_tex "tensor-with-ring-isomorphism" 'If $R$ is a ring with identity and $A_R$, ${}_R B$ are unitary $R$-modules, then there are $R$-module isomorphisms
\[
A \otimes_R R \cong A \quad \text{and} \quad R \otimes_R B \cong B.
\]'
write_intro "tensor-with-ring-isomorphism" "Tensoring with the base ring $R$ recovers the original module. The isomorphism $A \otimes_R R \cong A$ is given by $a \otimes r \mapsto ar$, with inverse $a \mapsto a \otimes 1_R$. This simple but crucial fact is the module-theoretic analogue of $a \times 1 = a$."

# Thm 5.8: Associativity of Tensor Product
write_yaml "associativity-of-tensor-product" "associativity-of-tensor-product" "Associativity of the Tensor Product" "张量积的结合性" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.5" "Theorem 5.8"
write_tex "associativity-of-tensor-product" 'Let $R$ and $S$ be rings and $A_R$, ${}_R B_S$, ${}_S C$ (bi)modules. Then there is an isomorphism of abelian groups
\[
(A \otimes_R B) \otimes_S C \cong A \otimes_R (B \otimes_S C)
\]
given by $(a \otimes b) \otimes c \mapsto a \otimes (b \otimes c)$.'
write_intro "associativity-of-tensor-product" "The tensor product is associative up to natural isomorphism. This allows unambiguous iteration of tensor products: $(A \otimes_R B) \otimes_S C$ and $A \otimes_R (B \otimes_S C)$ are naturally isomorphic via the map sending $(a \otimes b) \otimes c$ to $a \otimes (b \otimes c)$. The proof constructs mutual inverse homomorphisms using the universal property."
write_proof "associativity-of-tensor-product" "IV.5" "universal-property-iteration" 'The assignment $(\sum a_i \otimes b_i, c) \mapsto \sum a_i \otimes (b_i \otimes c)$ defines an $S$-middle linear map $(A \otimes_R B) \times C \to A \otimes_R (B \otimes_S C)$, inducing $\alpha: (A \otimes_R B) \otimes_S C \to A \otimes_R (B \otimes_S C)$ with $\alpha[(a \otimes b) \otimes c] = a \otimes (b \otimes c)$. Similarly, there is an $R$-middle linear map $A \times (B \otimes_S C) \to (A \otimes_R B) \otimes_S C$ inducing $\beta$ in the reverse direction. The compositions $\beta\alpha$ and $\alpha\beta$ are identity on generators, hence $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are isomorphisms.'

# Thm 5.9: Tensor Product Distributes over Direct Sums
write_yaml "tensor-product-distributivity-over-direct-sum" "tensor-product-distributivity-over-direct-sum" "Distributivity of Tensor Product over Direct Sums" "张量积对直和的分配性" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.5" "Theorem 5.9"
write_tex "tensor-product-distributivity-over-direct-sum" 'Let $R$ be a ring. There are isomorphisms of abelian groups:
\[
\left(\sum_{i \in I} A_i\right) \otimes_R B \cong \sum_{i \in I} (A_i \otimes_R B) \quad \text{and} \quad A \otimes_R \left(\sum_{j \in J} B_j\right) \cong \sum_{j \in J} (A \otimes_R B_j).
\]'
write_intro "tensor-product-distributivity-over-direct-sum" "Theorem 5.9 states that the tensor product distributes over direct sums. This is a central structural result: tensoring with a direct sum decomposes into a direct sum of tensor products. The proof constructs explicit isomorphisms using the canonical injections and projections of the direct sum, together with the universal property of the tensor product."
write_proof "tensor-product-distributivity-over-direct-sum" "IV.5" "canonical-maps" 'For the first isomorphism, define $\alpha: (\sum A_i) \otimes B \to \sum (A_i \otimes B)$ by $\alpha(\{a_i\} \otimes b) = \{a_i \otimes b\}_{i \in I}$ and $\beta: \sum (A_i \otimes B) \to (\sum A_i) \otimes B$ by $\beta(\{a_i \otimes b_i\}) = \sum \iota_i(a_i) \otimes b_i$. Verify $\alpha\beta$ and $\beta\alpha$ are identities using the fact that every element of $\sum A_i$ is $\sum \iota_i \pi_i(u)$. The second isomorphism is similar.'

# Thm 5.10: Hom-Tensor Adjunction
write_yaml "hom-tensor-adjunction" "hom-tensor-adjunction" "Adjoint Associativity (Hom-Tensor Adjunction)" "Hom-张量伴随性" "theorem" "module-theory" "advanced" "IV.5" "Theorem 5.10"
write_tex "hom-tensor-adjunction" 'Let $R$ and $S$ be rings and $A_R$, ${}_R B_S$, ${}_S C$ (bi)modules. Then there is an isomorphism of abelian groups
\[
\operatorname{Hom}_S(A \otimes_R B, C) \cong \operatorname{Hom}_R(A, \operatorname{Hom}_S(B, C)).
\]'
write_intro "hom-tensor-adjunction" "The Hom-Tensor adjunction (also called adjoint associativity or tensor-hom adjunction) is one of the most important isomorphisms in module theory. It states that $\operatorname{Hom}_S(A \otimes_R B, C)$ and $\operatorname{Hom}_R(A, \operatorname{Hom}_S(B, C))$ are naturally isomorphic. This adjunction is the foundation of much of homological algebra and category theory."

# Thm 5.11: Tensor with Free Module
write_yaml "tensor-with-free-module-structure" "tensor-with-free-module-structure" "Structure of the Tensor Product with a Free Module" "与自由模的张量积的结构" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.5" "Theorem 5.11"
write_tex "tensor-with-free-module-structure" 'Let $R$ be a ring with identity. If $A$ is a unitary right $R$-module and $F$ is a free left $R$-module with basis $Y$, then every element $u$ of $A \otimes_R F$ may be written uniquely in the form $u = \sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i \otimes y_i$, where $a_i \in A$ and the $y_i$ are distinct elements of $Y$.'
write_intro "tensor-with-free-module-structure" "Theorem 5.11 describes the explicit structure of the tensor product when one factor is free: every element can be written uniquely as a finite sum $\sum a_i \otimes y_i$ with distinct basis elements $y_i$. This is proved by constructing an isomorphism between $A \otimes_R F$ and the direct sum of copies of $A$ indexed by the basis $Y$."
write_proof "tensor-with-free-module-structure" "IV.5" "direct-sum-isomorphism" 'For each $y \in Y$, let $A_y$ be a copy of $A$ and consider $\sum_{y \in Y} A_y$. Since $\{y\}$ is linearly independent, $\varphi: R \to Ry$ given by $r \mapsto ry$ is an isomorphism. This induces an isomorphism $A \otimes_R R \to A \otimes_R Ry$, and composing with $A \otimes_R R \cong A$ (Theorem 5.7) gives an isomorphism $A \cong A \otimes_R Ry$. Summing over $y \in Y$ and using distributivity (Theorem 5.9) yields $A \otimes_R F \cong \sum A_y$. Under this isomorphism, $a \otimes y$ corresponds to $a$ in the $y$-th coordinate.'

# Thm 5.12: Tensor Product of Free Modules is Free
write_yaml "tensor-product-of-free-modules-is-free" "tensor-product-of-free-modules-is-free" "Tensor Product of Free Modules is Free" "自由模的张量积是自由模" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.5" "Theorem 5.12"
write_tex "tensor-product-of-free-modules-is-free" 'Let $R$ be a ring with identity. If $A$ is a free right $R$-module with basis $X$ and $B$ is a free left $R$-module with basis $Y$, then $A \otimes_R B$ is a free right $R$-module (left $R$-module) with basis $\{x \otimes y \mid x \in X, y \in Y\}$ of cardinality $|X||Y|$.'
write_intro "tensor-product-of-free-modules-is-free" "Theorem 5.12 establishes that the tensor product of free modules is again free, with basis given by the pairwise tensor products of the original bases. The rank of the tensor product is the product of the ranks. This is used extensively in algebraic topology and geometry."

# Cor 5.13: Extension of Scalars for Free Modules
write_yaml "extension-of-scalars-for-free-modules" "extension-of-scalars-for-free-modules" "Extension of Scalars for Free Modules" "自由模的标量扩张" "corollary" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.5" "Corollary 5.13"
write_tex "extension-of-scalars-for-free-modules" 'Let $S$ be a ring with identity and $R$ a subring of $S$ that contains $1_S$. If $F$ is a free left $R$-module with basis $X$, then $S \otimes_R F$ is a free left $S$-module with basis $\{1_S \otimes x \mid x \in X\}$ of cardinality $|X|$.'
write_intro "extension-of-scalars-for-free-modules" "Corollary 5.13 describes extension of scalars: given a free module $F$ over a subring $R$ of $S$, tensoring with $S$ over $R$ yields a free $S$-module of the same rank. This is the module-theoretic analogue of extending a vector space from $\mathbb{R}$ to $\mathbb{C}$ by tensoring."

