# Thm 6.1: Submodules of Free Modules over PID are Free
write_yaml "submodules-of-free-modules-over-pid-are-free" "submodules-of-free-modules-over-pid-are-free" "Submodules of Free Modules over a PID are Free" "PID上自由模的子模是自由模" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.6" "Theorem 6.1"
write_tex "submodules-of-free-modules-over-pid-are-free" 'Let $R$ be a principal ideal domain. Then every submodule $G$ of a free $R$-module $F$ is itself a free $R$-module, and $\operatorname{rank} G \leq \operatorname{rank} F$.'
write_intro "submodules-of-free-modules-over-pid-are-free" "Theorem 6.1 is a cornerstone result: over a principal ideal domain, submodules of free modules are free. This generalizes the fact that subgroups of free abelian groups are free, and is essential for the structure theory of finitely generated modules over PIDs. The proof uses a well-ordering of the basis of $F$ and shows each $G_{i+1}/G_i$ is isomorphic to an ideal of $R$, hence free of rank 0 or 1."
write_proof "submodules-of-free-modules-over-pid-are-free" "IV.6" "filtration-by-rank" 'Let $X = \{x_i\}_{i \in I}$ be a basis of $F$. Well-order $I$ and define $F_j = \sum_{k < j} R x_k$, $G_j = G \cap F_j$. Then (i) $F_{i+1}/F_i \cong R$; (ii) $G_{i+1}/G_i \cong (G_{i+1} + F_i)/F_i$ is a submodule of $R$, hence an ideal of $R$, so $G_{i+1}/G_i$ is free of rank 0 or 1. Using split exact sequences, each $G_{i+1} = G_i \oplus R b_i$ for some $b_i$, and by transfinite induction $G$ is a direct sum of rank-0 or rank-1 free modules, hence free.'

# Thm 6.3: Projective iff Free over PID (finitely generated case)
write_yaml "projective-iff-free-over-pid" "projective-iff-free-over-pid" "Finitely Generated Modules over a PID: Projective iff Free" "PID上有限生成模：投射当且仅当自由" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.6" "Theorem 6.3"
write_tex "projective-iff-free-over-pid" 'Let $R$ be a principal ideal domain. A finitely generated $R$-module $A$ is projective if and only if it is free.'
write_intro "projective-iff-free-over-pid" "Theorem 6.3 states that for finitely generated modules over a PID, the notions of projective and free coincide. Since free modules are always projective (Theorem 3.2), the nontrivial direction uses the fact that a projective module is a direct summand of a free module, and submodules of free modules over a PID are free (Theorem 6.1)."

# Thm 6.4: Order Ideal and Torsion Submodule
write_yaml "order-ideal-and-torsion-submodule" "order-ideal-and-torsion-submodule" "Order Ideal and the Torsion Submodule" "阶理想与挠子模" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.6" "Theorem 6.4"
write_tex "order-ideal-and-torsion-submodule" 'Let $A$ be a left module over an integral domain $R$ and for each $a \in A$ let $\mathcal{O}_a = \{r \in R \mid ra = 0\}$.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $\mathcal{O}_a$ is an ideal of $R$ for each $a \in A$.
\item[(ii)] $A_t = \{a \in A \mid \mathcal{O}_a \neq 0\}$ is a submodule of $A$ (the \emph{torsion submodule}).
\item[(iii)] For each $a \in A$ there is an isomorphism of left modules $R/\mathcal{O}_a \cong Ra = \{ra \mid r \in R\}$.
\item[(iv)] If $R$ is a PID, $p \in R$ prime, and $p^i a = 0$, then $\mathcal{O}_a = (p^j)$ with $0 \leq j \leq i$.
\item[(v)] If $\mathcal{O}_a = (p^i)$, then $p^j a \neq 0$ for all $j$ with $0 \leq j < i$.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "order-ideal-and-torsion-submodule" "Theorem 6.4 introduces the order ideal $\mathcal{O}_a = \{r \mid ra = 0\}$, which generalizes the order of an element in a group. The torsion submodule $A_t$ consists of elements with nonzero order ideals. Over a PID, the order ideal of an element annihilated by a prime power is itself a prime power ideal, and the cyclic module generated by $a$ is isomorphic to $R/\mathcal{O}_a$."
write_proof "order-ideal-and-torsion-submodule" "IV.6" "ideal-arithmetic" '(iii) The map $R \to Ra$ given by $r \mapsto ra$ is an $R$-module epimorphism with kernel $\mathcal{O}_a$, so $R/\mathcal{O}_a \cong Ra$ by Theorem 1.7. (iv) Over a PID, $\mathcal{O}_a = (r)$. Since $p^i a = 0$, $p^i \in \mathcal{O}_a$, so $r \mid p^i$, hence $r = p^j$ for some $0 \leq j \leq i$.'

# Thm 6.5: Finitely Generated Torsion-Free over PID is Free
write_yaml "finitely-generated-torsion-free-over-pid-is-free" "finitely-generated-torsion-free-over-pid-is-free" "Finitely Generated Torsion-Free Modules over a PID are Free" "PID上有限生成无挠模是自由模" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.6" "Theorem 6.5"
write_tex "finitely-generated-torsion-free-over-pid-is-free" 'A finitely generated torsion-free module $A$ over a principal ideal domain $R$ is free.'
write_intro "finitely-generated-torsion-free-over-pid-is-free" "Theorem 6.5 is a key structural result: over a PID, finitely generated torsion-free modules are free. This generalizes the fact that finitely generated torsion-free abelian groups are free. The proof selects a maximal linearly independent subset of a generating set and shows it spans after multiplying by suitable scalars."
write_proof "finitely-generated-torsion-free-over-pid-is-free" "IV.6" "maximal-independent-subset" 'Assume $A \neq 0$. Let $X$ be a finite set of generators and $S = \{x_1,\ldots,x_k\}$ a maximal subset of $X$ that is linearly independent. $F = \langle S \rangle$ is free with basis $S$. For each $y \in X - S$, by maximality there exist $r_y, r_1,\ldots,r_k$ not all zero with $r_y y + \sum r_i x_i = 0$, and $r_y \neq 0$ (since $S$ is independent). Let $r = \prod r_y$ over all $y \in X - S$. Then $rA \subset F$. Since $A$ is torsion-free, the map $a \mapsto ra$ is an $R$-module monomorphism $A \to F$. By Theorem 6.1, $rA \cong A$ is free.'

# Thm 6.6: Torsion-Torsion-Free Decomposition
write_yaml "torsion-torsion-free-decomposition" "torsion-torsion-free-decomposition" "Decomposition into Torsion and Torsion-Free Parts" "挠部分与无挠部分的分解" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.6" "Theorem 6.6"
write_tex "torsion-torsion-free-decomposition" 'If $A$ is a finitely generated module over a principal ideal domain $R$, then $A = A_t \oplus F$, where $A_t$ is the torsion submodule of $A$ and $F$ is a free $R$-module of finite rank. The rank of $F$ is uniquely determined by $A$.'
write_intro "torsion-torsion-free-decomposition" "Theorem 6.6 provides the fundamental decomposition of a finitely generated module over a PID into its torsion part and a free part. The quotient $A/A_t$ is torsion-free, hence free (by Theorem 6.5). The exact sequence $0 \to A_t \to A \to A/A_t \to 0$ splits, yielding $A \cong A_t \oplus (A/A_t)$ with free complement."

# Thm 6.7: Primary Decomposition of Torsion Module
write_yaml "primary-decomposition-of-torsion-module" "primary-decomposition-of-torsion-module" "Primary Decomposition of a Torsion Module over a PID" "PID上挠模的准素分解" "theorem" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.6" "Theorem 6.7"
write_tex "primary-decomposition-of-torsion-module" 'Let $A$ be a torsion module over a principal ideal domain $R$ and for each prime $p \in R$ let $A(p) = \{a \in A \mid a \text{ has order a power of } p\}$.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $A(p)$ is a submodule of $A$ for each prime $p \in R$;
\item[(ii)] $A = \sum A(p)$, where the sum is over all primes $p \in R$. If $A$ is finitely generated, only finitely many $A(p)$ are nonzero.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "primary-decomposition-of-torsion-module" "Theorem 6.7 decomposes a torsion module into its $p$-primary components $A(p)$, each consisting of elements annihilated by some power of the prime $p$. This generalizes the primary decomposition of finite abelian groups. The proof uses the Chinese Remainder Theorem (Theorem III.3.11) to express $1_R$ as a linear combination of co-prime elements annihilating the components."
write_proof "primary-decomposition-of-torsion-module" "IV.6" "chinese-remainder" '(i) If $a,b \in A(p)$ with orders $p^r$ and $p^s$, then $p^{\max(r,s)}(a+b) = 0$, so $a+b \in A(p)$. Similarly, $ra \in A(p)$ for $r \in R$.

(ii) Let $0 \neq a \in A$ with $\mathcal{O}_a = (r)$. Factor $r = p_1^{n_1} \cdots p_k^{n_k}$. Let $r_i = r/p_i^{n_i}$. These are relatively prime, so there exist $s_1,\ldots,s_k \in R$ with $\sum s_i r_i = 1_R$ (Theorem III.3.11). Then $a = 1_R a = \sum s_i r_i a$, and $p_i^{n_i}(s_i r_i a) = s_i r a = 0$, so $s_i r_i a \in A(p_i)$. Hence $A = \sum A(p)$.'

# Lemma 6.8: Cyclic Prime Power Order Properties
write_yaml "cyclic-prime-power-order-properties" "cyclic-prime-power-order-properties" "Properties of Cyclic Modules of Prime Power Order" "素幂阶循环模的性质" "lemma" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.6" "Lemma 6.8"
write_tex "cyclic-prime-power-order-properties" 'Let $A$ be a cyclic module of order $p^n$ ($p$ prime) over a principal ideal domain $R$, and let $a$ be a generator of $A$. Then:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] for every nonzero $b \in A$, there exists a nonnegative integer $j \leq n$ and $c \in A$ such that $Ra \cap Rb = 0$, $p^{j-1}c \notin Ra$ (if $j \geq 1$), and $b = rc + p^k a$ for some $r,k \in R$ not divisible by $p$;
\item[(ii)] there exists a submodule $C$ of $A$ maximal with respect to $Ra \cap C = 0$, and then $A = Ra \oplus C$ (so $C$ is cyclic of order $p^m$ with $m \leq n$).
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "cyclic-prime-power-order-properties" "Lemma 6.8 analyzes the structure of cyclic modules of prime power order, providing key technical results used in the proof of the structure theorem (Theorem 6.12). It shows that such modules can be decomposed as a direct sum of a given cyclic submodule and a complementary cyclic submodule."

# Lemma 6.9: Cyclic Summand Existence
write_yaml "cyclic-summand-existence" "cyclic-summand-existence" "Existence of Cyclic Summands" "循环直和项的存在性" "lemma" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.6" "Lemma 6.9"
write_tex "cyclic-summand-existence" 'Let $A$ be a finitely generated torsion module of order $p^n$ ($p$ prime) over a principal ideal domain $R$. Then $A$ is a direct sum of cyclic $R$-modules of orders $p^{n_1}, \ldots, p^{n_k}$ with $n_1 \geq n_2 \geq \cdots \geq n_k \geq 1$ and $\sum n_i = n$.'
write_intro "cyclic-summand-existence" "Lemma 6.9 proves that every finitely generated $p$-primary torsion module decomposes as a direct sum of cyclic modules of prime power orders. The cyclic summands can be arranged so that their orders are non-increasing. This is proved by induction on the exponent $n$ using Lemma 6.8."

# Lemma 6.10: Properties of rA and A[r]
write_yaml "properties-of-ra-and-ar" "properties-of-ra-and-ar" "Properties of rA and A[r]" "rA与A[r]的性质" "lemma" "module-theory" "intermediate" "IV.6" "Lemma 6.10"
write_tex "properties-of-ra-and-ar" 'Let $A,B,$ and $A_i$ ($i \in I$) be modules over a principal ideal domain $R$. Let $r \in R$ and let $p \in R$ be prime.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $rA = \{ra \mid a \in A\}$ and $A[r] = \{a \in A \mid ra = 0\}$ are submodules of $A$.
\item[(ii)] $R/(p)$ is a field and $A[p]$ is a vector space over $R/(p)$.
\item[(iii)] For each positive integer $n$ there are $R$-module isomorphisms $(R/(p^n))[p] \cong R/(p)$ and $p^m(R/(p^n)) \cong R/(p^{n-m})$ ($0 \leq m < n$).
\item[(iv)] If $A \cong \sum A_i$, then $rA \cong \sum rA_i$ and $A[r] \cong \sum A_i[r]$.
\item[(v)] If $f: A \to B$ is an $R$-module isomorphism, then $f: A_t \cong B_t$ and $f: A(p) \cong B(p)$.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "properties-of-ra-and-ar" "Lemma 6.10 collects essential technical properties of the submodules $rA$ (multiples) and $A[r]$ ($r$-torsion). Over a PID, $R/(p)$ is a field by Theorem III.2.20 and III.3.4, making $A[p]$ a vector space. The isomorphisms in (iii) are key to the uniqueness proof in the structure theorem."

# Thm 6.12: Structure Theorem for Finitely Generated Modules over a PID
write_yaml "structure-theorem-fg-modules-over-pid" "structure-theorem-fg-modules-over-pid" "Structure Theorem for Finitely Generated Modules over a PID" "PID上有限生成模的结构定理" "theorem" "module-theory" "advanced" "IV.6" "Theorem 6.12"
write_tex "structure-theorem-fg-modules-over-pid" 'Let $A$ be a finitely generated module over a principal ideal domain $R$.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $A$ is the direct sum of a free submodule $F$ of finite rank and a finite number of cyclic torsion modules of orders $r_1,\ldots,r_t$, where $r_1,\ldots,r_t$ are nonzero nonunit elements of $R$ such that $r_1 \mid r_2 \mid \cdots \mid r_t$. The rank of $F$ and the list of ideals $(r_1),\ldots,(r_t)$ are uniquely determined by $A$ (the \emph{invariant factors}).
\item[(ii)] $A$ is the direct sum of a free submodule $E$ of finite rank and a finite number of cyclic torsion modules of orders $p_1^{s_1},\ldots,p_k^{s_k}$, where $p_1,\ldots,p_k$ are primes in $R$ and $s_1,\ldots,s_k$ are positive integers. The rank of $E$ and the list of ideals $(p_1^{s_1}),\ldots,(p_k^{s_k})$ are uniquely determined by $A$ up to order (the \emph{elementary divisors}).
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "structure-theorem-fg-modules-over-pid" "Theorem 6.12 is the fundamental structure theorem for finitely generated modules over principal ideal domains, generalizing the classification of finitely generated abelian groups. Every such module decomposes into a free part (of well-defined rank) and a torsion part, which further decomposes either by invariant factors (with divisibility conditions) or by elementary divisors (prime power orders). Both decompositions provide complete sets of isomorphism invariants."

# Cor 6.13: Classification
write_yaml "classification-fg-modules-over-pid" "classification-fg-modules-over-pid" "Classification of Finitely Generated Modules over a PID" "PID上有限生成模的分类" "corollary" "module-theory" "advanced" "IV.6" "Corollary 6.13"
write_tex "classification-fg-modules-over-pid" 'Two finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain, $A$ and $B$, are isomorphic if and only if $A/A_t$ and $B/B_t$ have the same rank and $A$ and $B$ have the same invariant factors (resp. elementary divisors).'
write_intro "classification-fg-modules-over-pid" "Corollary 6.13 gives a complete classification of finitely generated modules over a PID up to isomorphism: two such modules are isomorphic exactly when their free parts have the same rank and their torsion parts share the same invariant factors (or elementary divisors). This is the module-theoretic analogue of the classification of finite abelian groups."

