# Def 7.1: K-Algebra
write_yaml "k-algebra" "k-algebra" "K-Algebra" "K-代数" "definition" "algebra" "basic" "IV.7" "Definition 7.1"
write_tex "k-algebra" 'Let $K$ be a commutative ring with identity. A \emph{$K$-algebra} (or \emph{algebra over $K$}) $A$ is a ring $A$ such that:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] $(A,+)$ is a unitary (left) $K$-module;
\item[(ii)] $k(ab) = (ka)b = a(kb)$ for all $k \in K$ and $a,b \in A$.
\end{enumerate}
A $K$-algebra $A$ which, as a ring, is a division ring, is called a \emph{division algebra}. An algebra over a field $K$ that is finite dimensional as a vector space over $K$ is called a \emph{finite dimensional algebra over $K$}.'
write_intro "k-algebra" "A $K$-algebra is simultaneously a ring and a $K$-module, with the scalar multiplication compatible with the ring multiplication: scalars commute with ring elements in the sense that $k(ab) = (ka)b = a(kb)$. Familiar examples include polynomial rings, matrix rings, and field extensions. When $K$ is a field, an algebra is a vector space equipped with a bilinear multiplication."

# Thm 7.2: Algebra Structure via Tensor Product
write_yaml "algebra-structure-via-tensor-product" "algebra-structure-via-tensor-product" "Algebra Structure via Tensor Product" "通过张量积刻画代数结构" "theorem" "module-theory" "advanced" "IV.7" "Theorem 7.2"
write_tex "algebra-structure-via-tensor-product" 'Let $K$ be a commutative ring with identity and $A$ a unitary left $K$-module. Then $A$ is a $K$-algebra if and only if there exists a $K$-module homomorphism $\pi : A \otimes_K A \to A$ (the \emph{product map}) such that the associativity diagram commutes. In this case $A$ has an identity if and only if there is a $K$-module homomorphism $I : K \to A$ (the \emph{unit map}) such that the unit diagram commutes (with the isomorphisms $K \otimes_K A \cong A \cong A \otimes_K K$).'
write_intro "algebra-structure-via-tensor-product" "Theorem 7.2 gives a categorical/tensor-theoretic characterization of algebras. A $K$-module $A$ is a $K$-algebra precisely when it is equipped with an associative product map $\pi: A \otimes_K A \to A$ (which encodes the multiplication $ab = \pi(a \otimes b)$), and is unital when there is a unit map $I: K \to A$ (sending $1_K$ to $1_A$). This perspective is fundamental in the theory of coalgebras and Hopf algebras."
write_proof "algebra-structure-via-tensor-product" "IV.7" "tensor-characterization" 'If $A$ is a $K$-algebra, the map $A \times A \to A$, $(a,b) \mapsto ab$, is $K$-bilinear, hence induces a $K$-module homomorphism $\pi: A \otimes_K A \to A$ by Theorem 5.6. Associativity of multiplication translates to commutativity of the diagram. If $A$ has identity $1_A$, define $I: K \to A$ by $k \mapsto k1_A$. Conversely, given $\pi$, define $ab = \pi(a \otimes b)$ and verify the $K$-algebra axioms; given $I$, $I(1_K)$ is the identity.'

# Def 7.3: Algebra Homomorphism and Algebra Ideal
write_yaml "algebra-homomorphism-and-algebra-ideal" "algebra-homomorphism-and-algebra-ideal" "Algebra Homomorphism and Algebra Ideal" "代数同态与代数理想" "definition" "algebra" "basic" "IV.7" "Definition 7.3"
write_tex "algebra-homomorphism-and-algebra-ideal" 'Let $K$ be a commutative ring with identity and $A$, $B$ $K$-algebras.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] A function $f: A \to B$ is a \emph{$K$-algebra homomorphism} if $f$ is both a ring homomorphism and a $K$-module homomorphism.
\item[(ii)] A subset $I$ of $A$ is a \emph{$K$-algebra ideal} (or \emph{algebra ideal}) if $I$ is both a ring ideal and a $K$-submodule. If $A$ has an identity, every (left, right, two-sided) ideal is also an algebra ideal.
\end{enumerate}'
write_intro "algebra-homomorphism-and-algebra-ideal" "Definition 7.3 extends the notions of homomorphism and ideal to the algebra setting. An algebra homomorphism must respect both the ring structure and the scalar multiplication (i.e., be $K$-linear). An algebra ideal is simultaneously a ring ideal and a $K$-submodule. Over unital algebras, all ideals are automatically algebra ideals."

# Thm 7.4: Tensor Product of Algebras
write_yaml "tensor-product-of-algebras" "tensor-product-of-algebras" "Tensor Product of Algebras" "代数的张量积" "theorem" "algebra" "intermediate" "IV.7" "Theorem 7.4"
write_tex "tensor-product-of-algebras" 'Let $A$ and $B$ be algebras [with identity] over a commutative ring $K$ with identity. Let $\pi$ be the composition
\[
(A \otimes_K B) \otimes_K (A \otimes_K B) \xrightarrow{1_A \otimes \alpha \otimes 1_B} (A \otimes_K A) \otimes_K (B \otimes_K B) \xrightarrow{\pi_A \otimes \pi_B} A \otimes_K B,
\]
where $\pi_A, \pi_B$ are the product maps of $A$ and $B$ respectively, and $\alpha(a \otimes b) = b \otimes a$. Then $A \otimes_K B$ is a $K$-algebra [with identity] with product map $\pi$. For generators, $(a \otimes b)(a_1 \otimes b_1) = aa_1 \otimes bb_1$, and if $A,B$ have identities, $1_A \otimes 1_B$ is the identity.'
write_intro "tensor-product-of-algebras" "Theorem 7.4 constructs the tensor product of two $K$-algebras, which is again a $K$-algebra. The multiplication is defined componentwise on elementary tensors: $(a \otimes b)(a_1 \otimes b_1) = aa_1 \otimes bb_1$, using the swap map $\alpha$ to align the factors correctly. The product map $\pi$ factors through the associativity and commutativity constraints of the tensor product."

